window.EPA_QUESTION_BANKS={"core":[{"id":"core-001","group":"core","question":"Do natural events like volcanic eruptions contribute to chlorine in the stratosphere?","choices":["Yes, chlorine in the stratosphere is primarily from natural sources such as volcanoes","Yes, chlorine can come from natural sources such as volcanoes, but they are not the primary source","No, all chlorine comes from refrigerants released","There is no chlorine in the stratosphere"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Chlorine is released from natural sources such as volcanoes. But the primary reason for the rise of chlorine in the atmosphere is the refrigerants that have been released."},{"id":"core-002","group":"core","question":"Ground level ozone is what absorbs and reflects harmful UV rays from the sun.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Ozone in the Stratosphere absorbs and reflects harmful UV rays from the sun, not ground level ozone. Ground level ozone is actually harmful for humans when inhaled."},{"id":"core-003","group":"core","question":"In which of the following ways does ozone depletion affect humans? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Increased risk of heart disease","Increased risk of skin cancer","Increased risk of pancreatic cancer","Increased risk of cataracts"],"answer":1,"explanation":"When ozone is depleted, less ozone is available to absorb harmful UV radiation from the sun, increasing the risk of skin cancer and cataracts in humans."},{"id":"core-004","group":"core","question":"Is there evidence that refrigerants are in the stratosphere?","choices":["Yes","No","Inconclusive"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Yes, air samples taken from the stratosphere confirm that refrigerants such as CFCs and HCFCs make it to the stratosphere, where they destroy ozone."},{"id":"core-005","group":"core","question":"Which of the following statements is TRUE about chlorine?","choices":["chlorine atom can only bond once with an oxygen atom","single chlorine atom can survive in the atmosphere for vO years","Chlorine creates carbon monoxide when it destroys ozone molecules","chlorine atom disintegrates quickly in the atmosphere"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A single chlorine atom can remain in the atmosphere for years and repeatedly participate in ozone-depleting reactions."},{"id":"core-006","group":"core","question":"Ozone has __ atoms of oxygen.","choices":["2","3","8","10"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Ozone is composed of 3 atoms of oxygen."},{"id":"core-007","group":"core","question":"The majority of Earth's ozone is located in the stratosphere.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Most of Earth's ozone is located in the stratosphere, where it forms the ozone layer. This layer absorbs much of the Sun's harmful ultraviolet (UV) radiation."},{"id":"core-008","group":"core","question":"How many molecules of ozone can three chlorine atoms destroy?","choices":["3,000","100,000","300,000","1,000,000"],"answer":2,"explanation":"In ozone depletion, chlorine acts as individual atoms, not as intact molecules. One chlorine atom can destroy approximately 100,000 molecules of ozone through catalytic reactions. Since the question refers to three chlorine atoms, they can destroy 3 x 100,000 = 300,000 ozone molecules."},{"id":"core-009","group":"core","question":"What is the major function of ozone in the stratosphere?","choices":["Absorb and reflect UV rays from the sun","Create UV rays by using rays from the sun","Direct UV rays from the sun to humans","Convert UV rays into energy for humans"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Ozone is essential to life on earth because it absorbs and reflects harmful UV rays from the sun."},{"id":"core-010","group":"core","question":"What is the primary source of chlorine in the stratosphere?","choices":["Volcanoes","Natural sources such as earthquakes","Emissions of refrigerant chemicals such as CFCs and HCFCs by humans","There is no chlorine in the stratosphere"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The primary source of the rise of chlorine in the atmosphere Is the refrigerants that have been released by humans."},{"id":"core-011","group":"core","question":"Which element is primarily responsible for stratospheric ozone depletion?","choices":["Carbon","Chlorine","Calcium","Fluorine"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Chlorine is the element in many older refrigerants that harms the ozone layer. In the stratosphere, released chlorine atoms break down ozone repeatedly."},{"id":"core-012","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are effects of ozone depletion?","choices":["Increasing toxicity in the oceans","Increasing acidity in the air","Decreasing crop yields","Increasing crop yields"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Decreasing crop yields is an effect of ozone depletion. This is due to increased UV rays from the sun that damage plant life."},{"id":"core-013","group":"core","question":"Which refrigerant chemicals are responsible for the destruction of the ozone layer?","choices":["CFCs and HCFCs","Chlorine and ozone","HFCs and carbon dioxide","CFCs and oxygen"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The refrigerant chemicals that are responsible for ozone depletion are CFCs (chlorofluorocarbons) and HCFCs (hydrochlorofluorocarbons)"},{"id":"core-014","group":"core","question":"Who does ozone depletion affect?","choices":["People close to areas with a lot of ozone","People in the United States","People in high altitudes","People all over the world"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Ozone depletion is a global problem and affects everyone living on earth."},{"id":"core-015","group":"core","question":"After a refrigerant is phased out, can technicians still service existing systems that use it?","choices":["Yes, if they are 608 certified and use recovered or reclaimed refrigerant","No, all equipment must be replaced immediately","Yes, anyone can service it as long as they can obtain refrigerant","No, phased-out refrigerants are completely illegal to handle"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Phasing out a refrigerant means that it can no longer be produced or imported. Technicians can still service equipment that contains that refrigerant, but those technicians need to be Section 608 certified."},{"id":"core-016","group":"core","question":"In 2025, a technician repairs an R-22 system and needs to add refrigerant to finish the job. Since new production and imports are banned, which sources are allowed for servicing this equipment? (Select all that apply) :","choices":["From another state with fewer restrictions","From importing new R-22","From stock recovered R-22 refrigerant only if recovered from the same customer's system","From stock reclaimed R-22"],"answer":2,"explanation":"After a refrigerant is phased out, technicians still need to service systems that contain that refrigerant. To service existing equipment, service refrigerant must come from recovered or reclaimed supplies."},{"id":"core-017","group":"core","question":"Under EPA Section 608, can used ozone-depleting refrigerants and non-exempt substitute refrigerants be resold to a new owner?","choices":["Yes, but only if it has been reclaimed by an EPA-certified reclaimer to AHRI Standard 700 purity specifications","Yes, but only if it has been inspected by the EPA","Yes, all refrigerant can be resold","No"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Used Class I/II refrigerants and non-exempt substitutes generally cannot be resold unless reclaimed by an EPA- certified reclaimer to AHRI Standard 700 purity. (Exempt substitutes such as CO, are not the focus here.)"},{"id":"core-018","group":"core","question":"Equipment has to be certified to EPA standards in order to recover which of the following refrigerants? (Select all that apply)","choices":["CFCs","HCFCs","HFCs","All refrigerants"],"answer":0,"explanation":"All equipment used to recover ozone-depleting refrigerants or their substitutes must meet EPA standards. “Ozone-depleting refrigerants and their substitutes” include CFCs, HCFCs, and HFCs. Selecting ‘All refrigerants’ is too broad, as it includes exempt substitutes like CO2 (R- 744)."},{"id":"core-019","group":"core","question":"If you are selling R-22 refrigerant, who can you sell to? (Select all that apply)","choices":["An environmentalist","An EPA official","A technician with Section 608 certification","A business that employs a technician with Section 608 certification"],"answer":2,"explanation":"SY Y certification The sales restriction in Section 608 limits the sale of all ozone- depleting refrigerants and their substitutes to technicians with certification or their employers. R-22 is an HCFC refrigerant, so it falls in this category."},{"id":"core-020","group":"core","question":"If you recover R-12 refrigerant, can you use the recovered refrigerant in another device owned by a different person?","choices":["Yes, but only if it has been reclaimed to AHRI Standard 700 specifications","Yes, but only if it has been inspected by the EPA","Yes, all refrigerant can be resold","No, reclaimed refrigerant is illegal to use"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Using the refrigerant owned by a different person is considered changing ownership. So, to change ownership, the refrigerant has to be reclaimed according to AHRI Standard 700 specifications."},{"id":"core-021","group":"core","question":"In the United States, when were all CFCs phased out by?","choices":["1985","1990","1995","2000"],"answer":2,"explanation":"All CFCs were phased out in 1995."},{"id":"core-022","group":"core","question":"In the United States, when were R-22 and R-142b phased out?","choices":["1995","2000","2020","2030"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-22 and R-142b, along with the majority of HCFCs, were phased out on January 1, 2020. This means there can be no new production or imports of these refrigerants."},{"id":"core-023","group":"core","question":"In the United States, by what year will the complete HCFC phaseout be finalized under EPA regulations?","choices":["1995","2000","2020","2030"],"answer":3,"explanation":"While production and import of R-22 largely ended in 2020, the complete HCFC phaseout timeline in the United States extends through 2030."},{"id":"core-024","group":"core","question":"Which of the following information must be included in service records for equipment containing R-22 refrigerant? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Type of refrigerant used or recovered","Date of service","Quantity of refrigerant added or removed","Model number of the appliance"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Service records must document the type of refrigerant, the date of service, and the quantity of refrigerant added or removed. Recording the model number of the appliance is not required for refrigerant compliance records."},{"id":"core-025","group":"core","question":"Section 608 of the Clean Air Act is:","choices":["A set of federal guidelines on limiting air pollutants","Federal law","State law","A global treaty"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Section 608 of the Clean Air Act is a federal law."},{"id":"core-026","group":"core","question":"Which statements about state and local regulations are true? Select all that apply.","choices":["They must be followed in addition to federal CAA regulations","They replace federal CAA regulations","They may be stricter than federal CAA regulations","They are only suggestions"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Technicians must follow federal regulations along with any applicable state and local regulations. State and local rules may also be stricter than federal requirements."},{"id":"core-027","group":"core","question":"The Venting Prohibition requires that you recover affected refrigerant before (Select all that apply):","choices":["Opening equipment","Servicing equipment","Disposing of equipment","Manufacturing equipment"],"answer":0,"explanation":"It is necessary to recover refrigerant before opening, servicing, or disposing of refrigerant. This prevents the venting of refrigerant. You have correctly selected 2."},{"id":"core-028","group":"core","question":"Ascrap yard is taking in old rooftop units. Under Section 608, who must verify that all refrigerant has been removed before disposal?","choices":["The original installing contractor.","The EPA field inspector.","The equipment owner or technician","The final person in the disposal chain"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Section 608 dictates that the final person in the disposal chain must make sure that all refrigerant is removed from equipment before disposal. In practice, this would be the scrap metal recycler or the landfill owner."},{"id":"core-029","group":"core","question":"EPA Section 608 regulations apply to appliances that contain and use . refrigerant. Which of the following is covered?","choices":["Freezers","Desiccant dehumidifiers","Both (A) and (B)","None of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Section 608 applies to equipment that contains and uses refrigerant. Freezers are covered, while desiccant dehumidifiers typically do not use refrigerant."},{"id":"core-030","group":"core","question":"What does SNAP stand for?","choices":["Significant New Alternatives Policy","Science New Alliances Policy","Science Neutral Alliances Policy","None of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"SNAP stands for Significant New Alternatives Policy."},{"id":"core-031","group":"core","question":"On August 15, 2017, a contractor was cited for two separate Clean Air Act violations. If both violations continued for three days (Aug 15-17), what is the maximum total civil fine based on the 2017 penalty schedule?","choices":["$44,539","$89,078","$222,695","$267,234"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Under the 2017 Clean Air Act penalty schedule, each violation can be fined up to $44,539 per day. Since there were 2 violations lasting 3 days, that equals 6 total violation-days. 6 x $44,539 = $267,234."},{"id":"core-032","group":"core","question":"What change did the 2016 Kigali Amendment make to the Montreal Protocol?","choices":["Allowed limited CFC production again for servicing older equipment","Added a global phase-down schedule for HFCs due to their climate impact","Moved the HCFC phase-out completion date worldwide to 2010","It ended the use of HFCs immediately in every country"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Kigali Amendment expands the Montreal Protocol by adding a phasedown schedule for HEC production and consumption. HFCs don't deplete ozone, but they have high GWP."},{"id":"core-033","group":"core","question":"What is the purpose of Section 608? (Select all that apply)","choices":["To protect the ozone layer","To regulate use of chemicals that deplete ozone","To raise money through fines","Economic reasons"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The main provisions of Section 608 are to protect the ozone layer by regulating chemicals that destroy it."},{"id":"core-034","group":"core","question":"What is the purpose of SNAP? (Select all that apply)","choices":["To evaluate alternative refrigerants","To further the goals of the CAA","To consider effects of substitute refrigerants on humans","To consider effects of substitute refrigerants on the environment"],"answer":0,"explanation":"environment All of these statements are true."},{"id":"core-035","group":"core","question":"What do you do if you discover that you have added Refrigerant B to a system that contained Refrigerant A? Consider that Refrigerant A is ozone-depleting.","choices":["Vent the refrigerant","Recover the mixture in a separate recovery cylinder","Add more of Refrigerant B","Add more of Refrigerant"],"answer":1,"explanation":"lf you accidentally mix two refrigerants, you must recover the mixture in a separate recovery cylinder. You need a separate recovery cylinder because you don't want this mixture to contaminate the contents of other cylinders."},{"id":"core-036","group":"core","question":"Under EPA regulations, who may perform refrigerant recovery from small appliances prior to final disposal?","choices":["Any individual using EPA-approved recovery equipment","Only the manufacturer","Only certified technicians","Only the equipment installer"],"answer":0,"explanation":"For small appliances being prepared for final disposal, EPA regulations do not require technician certification, as long as EPA- approved refrigerant recovery equipment is properly used."},{"id":"core-037","group":"core","question":"What other appliances do Section 608 regulations apply to? (Select the best answer)","choices":["Commercial refrigeration equipment","Air conditioning equipment","Both of the above","None of the above"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Both commercial refrigeration equipment and air conditioning equipment can contain ozone-depleting substances. Section 608 regulations apply to equipment that contains any ozone-depleting refrigerant or its substitute."},{"id":"core-038","group":"core","question":"What penalties can technicians face if they violate the Clean Air Act? (Select all that apply)","choices":["They may lose their Section 608 certification","They may face federal charges","They may have to do community service","They may be fined"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Technicians violating the Clean Air Act, especially Section 608 on refrigerant handling, may face penalties including losing their certification, fines, and potential federal charges."},{"id":"core-040","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are excluded from Section 608 refrigerant management requirements? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Carbon dioxide","HFCs","Nitrogen","CFCs"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Carbon dioxide and nitrogen are excluded from Section 608 refrigerant management requirements because they are not regulated refrigerants under EPA Section 608. HFCs and CFCs are regulated under Section 608 and therefore are not excluded."},{"id":"core-041","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are violations of the CAA Venting Prohibition? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Release of refrigerants because appliances were not Yo recovered","Releasing isobutane while servicing equipment","Releasing HFC refrigerant because of catastrophic equipment failure","Refrigerants released when disconnecting non-low-loss"],"answer":3,"explanation":"hoses to service an appliance These are violations of the venting prohibition. Isobutane is exempted because it is a natural refrigerant and does not deplete ozone and Catastrophic failure of equipment is covered under de minimis, as long as all proper procedures were followed."},{"id":"core-042","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are considered natural refrigerants? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-290","R-600a","R-744","R-11"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-290 (propane), R-600a (isobutane), and R-744 (carbon dioxide) are all considered natural refrigerants. In contrast, R-11 is a chlorofluorocarbon (CFC) that has significant ozone depletion potential and is not classified as a natural refrigerant. You have correctly selected 2."},{"id":"core-043","group":"core","question":"Which of the following do you not need Section 608 certification to purchase?","choices":["Nitrogen","HFCs","CFCs","HCFCs"],"answer":0,"explanation":"You do not need EPA Section 608 certification to purchase nitrogen. The sales restriction under Section 608 only applies to ozone- depleting refrigerants and their substitutes. Nitrogen is a natural refrigerant and is not included in this category."},{"id":"core-044","group":"core","question":"Which of the following is a CFC? (Choose all that apply)","choices":["R-11","R-12","R-20","R-22"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-11 and R-12 are both CFCs."},{"id":"core-045","group":"core","question":"Which of the following is an HCFC?","choices":["R-11","R-12","R-20","R-22"],"answer":3,"explanation":"From this list, only R-22 is an example of a hydrochlorofluorocarbon (HCFC)."},{"id":"core-046","group":"core","question":"Which of the following refrigerants does the Venting Prohibition cover?","choices":["CFCs and HCFCs","CFCs, HCFCs, and HFCs","CFCs and natural refrigerants","All natural refrigerants"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The CAA Venting Prohibition extends to all ozone-depleting refrigerants and their substitutes. This includes CFCs, HCFCs, and HFCs."},{"id":"core-047","group":"core","question":"According to EPA requirements, recovery equipment used with R-12 must be certified to standards established by which organization?","choices":["OSHA","AHRI","ASHRAE","EPA"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Recovery equipment used with R-12 must be certified to performance standards established by AHRI (Air-Conditioning, Heating, and Refrigeration Institute). EPA regulations require certified recovery equipment to meet these standards."},{"id":"core-048","group":"core","question":"Who does not need to maintain proper records of refrigerants?","choices":["Wholesalers","The EPA","Reclaimers","Owners and technicians"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The EPA is not responsible for maintaining records of refrigerants."},{"id":"core-050","group":"core","question":"Equipment that uses nitrogen as a refrigerant is not subject to Section 608 requirements.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Equipment that uses natural refrigerants is not subject to Section 608 requirements. Only equipment that contains ozone-depleting refrigerants (and their substitutes) is subject to Section 608 requirements."},{"id":"core-051","group":"core","question":"As the temperature of a liquid increases, what phase does it turn into? (Assume constant pressure)","choices":["Solid","Liquid","Vapor","Water"],"answer":2,"explanation":"As the temperature of a liquid increases, it turns into vapor. For example, when water boils, it changes into steam, which is water vapor."},{"id":"core-052","group":"core","question":"or Which component has the opposite function to the condenser?","choices":["Evaporator","Compressor","Metering Device","Suction Line"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The component that has the opposite function to the condenser is the Evaporator. While the condenser releases heat from the refrigerant to change it from a vapor to a liquid, the evaporator absorbs heat from the indoor air to change the refrigerant from a liquid to a vapor."},{"id":"core-053","group":"core","question":"What is the condenser’s job?","choices":["To cool the high-pressure vapor","To heat the high-pressure vapor","To increase the pressure","To decrease the pressure"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The condenser plays a crucial role in the refrigeration cycle by reducing the temperature of the refrigerant. It does this by transferring the heat from the refrigerant to the outdoor air, which facilitates the condensation of the refrigerant from a high-pressure vapor to a high- pressure liquid."},{"id":"core-054","group":"core","question":"What is the function of the metering device?","choices":["To decrease pressure","To increase pressure","To increase temperature","All ofthe above"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The function of the metering device is to decrease pressure. It controls the flow of refrigerant into the evaporator, reducing its pressure and, as a consequence, its temperature, preparing the refrigerant to absorb heat in the evaporator."},{"id":"core-055","group":"core","question":"What is the state of the refrigerant when it enters the condenser?","choices":["High-pressure liquid","Low-pressure liquid","High-pressure vapor","Low-pressure vapor"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The refrigerant enters the condenser as a high pressure vapor from the compressor. It enters the compressor as a low pressure vapor before it is compressed into a high pressure vapor and sent into the condenser."},{"id":"core-056","group":"core","question":"Inside the metering device, what change does the refrigerant primarily undergo?","choices":["Pressure increases while it remains a vapor","Pressure decreases while it remains a liquid","Temperature rises and it condenses to liquid","It boils into vapor at higher pressure"],"answer":1,"explanation":"In the metering device, the refrigerant is fully liquid, and the device reduces its pressure. It remains liquid as it exits at low pressure."},{"id":"core-057","group":"core","question":"When refrigerant exits the metering device, what state is it in?","choices":["Low-pressure liquid","Low-pressure vapor","High-pressure liquid","High-pressure vapor"],"answer":0,"explanation":"When refrigerant exits the metering device, it is in a low-pressure liquid state. The metering device is responsible for regulating the flow of refrigerant into the evaporator. It achieves this by reducing the pressure of the refrigerant, which causes it to partially vaporize and become a low-pressure liquid."},{"id":"core-058","group":"core","question":"Hh Conneee Inside the compressor, what happens to the refrigerant?","choices":["Condenses to liquid at higher pressure","Freezes into a solid as it cools","Stays a vapor while pressure increases","Evaporates from liquid to vapor"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The compressor receives refrigerant as a superheated, low-pressure vapor from the evaporator. It raises the pressure and temperature without changing state, so the discharge leaves as a high-pressure, high-temperature vapor."},{"id":"core-059","group":"core","question":"When the refrigerant enters the evaporator, what state is it in?","choices":["Solid","Liquid","Vapor","Water"],"answer":1,"explanation":"When the refrigerant enters the evaporator, it is typically in a low- pressure, low-temperature liquid state."},{"id":"core-060","group":"core","question":"When the refrigerant exits the evaporator, what state is it in?","choices":["Solid","Liquid","Vapor","Water"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When the refrigerant exits the evaporator, it is in a vapor state. The heat absorbed from the indoor air causes the refrigerant to evaporate and change from a low-pressure liquid to a low-pressure vapor."},{"id":"core-061","group":"core","question":"What is the state of the refrigerant when it exits the evaporator?","choices":["Low-pressure liquid","High-pressure vapor","Low-pressure vapor","High-pressure liquid"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When the refrigerant exits the evaporator, it is in a low-pressure vapor state. The refrigerant absorbs heat from the indoor air, which causes it to evaporate and transform from a low-pressure liquid to a low-pressure vapor."},{"id":"core-062","group":"core","question":"At constant pressure, boiling requires the addition of heat.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"At constant pressure, adding heat will raise the temperature of the substance until it reaches its boiling point, where it begins to vaporize."},{"id":"core-063","group":"core","question":"Condensation happens when a gas Or vapor cools down and becomes a liquid.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Condensation occurs when a gas or vapor loses heat energy, causing its molecules to slow down and come closer together. As a result, the molecules transition from a gaseous state to a liquid state. This process is commonly observed when water vapor in the air cools down upon contact with a colder surface, such as a glass of cold water or a mirror, leading to the formation of water droplets on the surface."},{"id":"core-064","group":"core","question":"The boiling point of most refrigerants is 212 °F.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. The boiling point of most refrigerants is not 212°F (which is equivalent to 100°C), as this temperature corresponds to the boiling point of water at standard atmospheric pressure. Refrigerants typically have much lower boiling points, often below room temperature. For example, common refrigerants like R-134a and R-410A have boiling points around -26.3°C (-15.34°F) and -48.5°C (-55.3°F), respectively."},{"id":"core-065","group":"core","question":"The vapor leaving the compressor is lower in pressure than vapor entering the compressor.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. The vapor leaving the compressor Is higher in pressure than the vapor entering the compressor. The main function of the compressor in a refrigeration or air conditioning system is to increase the pressure (and temperature) of the refrigerant vapor."},{"id":"core-066","group":"core","question":"You are boiling a pot of water with the lid on. As the water heats up and Starts to boil, you notice that drops of water form on the bottom of the pot lid. This is an example of condensation.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. In this scenario, as the water in the pot heats up and reaches its boiling point, water vapor rises and comes into contact with the cooler surface of the pot lid. Since the lid is cooler than the water vapor, the vapor loses heat energy to the lid and condenses back into liquid water droplets. This process is indeed an example of condensation."},{"id":"core-067","group":"core","question":"Your air conditioning works by adding cold air into your house.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Air conditioning works by removing heat and moisture from the air inside a building, thereby cooling and dehumidifying it. It does not \"add cold air\" but rather removes heat energy from the indoor air, resulting in a cooler environment."},{"id":"core-068","group":"core","question":"B2 refrigerants are more dangerous than which of the following? (Select all that apply)","choices":["B1","B3","A1","A2"],"answer":0,"explanation":"B2 refrigerants have high toxicity (Class B) and flammability (Class 2). Since they are highly toxic, they are more dangerous than c) A1 and d) A2 refrigerants. Since they have low flammability, they are more dangerous than B1 refrigerants, which are not flammable (Class 1)."},{"id":"core-069","group":"core","question":"What does HCFC stand for?","choices":["Hydrocarbons","Hydrofluorocarbons","Hydrochlorofluorocarbons","Hydrochlorofluoros"],"answer":2,"explanation":"HCFCs are hydrochlorofluorocarbons."},{"id":"core-070","group":"core","question":"Other than fluorine and chlorine, what do HCFCs contain? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Hydrogen","Carbon","Helium","Calcium"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Think of the letters in HCFC. The H is for Hydrogen. The first C is for Chlorine. The F is for Fluorine. And the last C is for Carbon."},{"id":"core-071","group":"core","question":"Which of the following elements can be found in HCFCs? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Fluorine","Chlorine","Ceranium","Halon"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Think of the letters in HCFC. H stands for Hydrogen, the first C is for Chlorine, F is for Fluorine, and the last C stands for Carbon. These are the elements found in HCFCs."},{"id":"core-072","group":"core","question":"Other than hydrogen, which elements do HFCs contain? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Fluorine","Carbon","Cadmium","Chlorine"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Of the letters in HFC: The H is for Hydrogen. The F is for Fluorine. And the last C is for Carbon."},{"id":"core-073","group":"core","question":"What safety classification do HFO refrigerants typically fall under?","choices":["A2L","A2","B2","B2L"],"answer":0,"explanation":"HFO refrigerants are generally classified as A2L refrigerants."},{"id":"core-074","group":"core","question":"What does HFO stand for?","choices":["Hydrofluorocarbons","Hydrofluorooxygens","Hydrocarbons","Hydrofluoroolefins"],"answer":3,"explanation":"HFOs are hydrofluoroolefins."},{"id":"core-075","group":"core","question":"Which of the following do HFOs contain?","choices":["Hydrogen","Halon","Chlorine","Oxygen"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The H in HFO stands for hydrogen. The O does not stand for oxygen."},{"id":"core-076","group":"core","question":"Which of the following do HFOs contain? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Fluorine","Falon","Oxygen","Carbon"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The H in HFO stands for hydrogen. The F stands for Fluorine. The last element of HFOs is carbon, just like HFCs. The O does not tell you the name of an element in HFOs."},{"id":"core-077","group":"core","question":"Which statement is true about hydrocarbons?","choices":["Are generally A3 refrigerants","Have high toxicity","Have low flammability","Are safe to use because they are natural refrigerants"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Hydrocarbons are A3 refrigerants. This means they have low toxicity but are highly flammable. While they are non-ozone depleting, they must be handled with care due to their flammability."},{"id":"core-078","group":"core","question":"If a refrigerant has an ODP of 0.055, which of the following are true? (Select all that apply)","choices":["It contains chlorine","It might contain chlorine","It could be R-22","It could be R-1234yf"],"answer":0,"explanation":"lf a refrigerant has an ODP of anything greater than O, it must contain chlorine, since it is chlorine that is responsible for destroying ozone. Examples of this include R-11, which has an ODP of 1, and R-22, which has an ODP of 0.055. They both contain chlorine. You have correctly selected 1."},{"id":"core-079","group":"core","question":"R-410A has a GWP of about 2,088. What does this number mean?","choices":["It emits 2,088 kg CO, for every kilogram produced","It is 2,088x more ozone-depleting than CO, across 100 years","It has 2,088 ppm allowable concentration in occupied spaces","It traps roughly 2,088 x as much heat as the same mass of CO2 over 100 years"],"answer":3,"explanation":"GWP compares the heat absorbed by a gas to that of CO, over a 100-year time horizon. So a GWP near 2,088 means one kilogram of R-410A warms the atmosphere about 2,088 times as much as one kilogram of CO, over that period."},{"id":"core-080","group":"core","question":"Which one of the following refrigerants has the lowest global warming potential (GWP)?","choices":["R-12","R-22","R-410a","R-1234yf"],"answer":3,"explanation":"As we saw earlier with the chart, R-1234yf has the least GWP. It is an HFO refrigerant and has a GWP of only 4."},{"id":"core-081","group":"core","question":"R-12 has a GWP in which of the following ranges?","choices":["1-500","500-1000","1000-10,000","10,000-50,000"],"answer":3,"explanation":"R-12 has a GWP of 10,900. This means it has close to 11,000 more global warming potential than carbon dioxide.10,900 would fall between 10,000 and 50,000."},{"id":"core-082","group":"core","question":"R-12 is the same as:","choices":["CFC-12","CFC-11","HCFC-12","HFO-12"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-12 is a CFC. So it is the same as CFC-12."},{"id":"core-083","group":"core","question":"R-1234yf is the same as:","choices":["CFC-1234yf","HCFC-1234yf","HFC-1234yf","HFO-1234yf"],"answer":3,"explanation":"R-1234yf is an HFO. So it is the same as HFO-1234yf."},{"id":"core-084","group":"core","question":"R-134a is the same as:","choices":["CFC-134a","HCFC-134a","HFC-134a","HFO-134a"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-134a is an HFC. So it is the same as HFC-134a."},{"id":"core-085","group":"core","question":"R-410a has a GWP in which of the following ranges?","choices":["1-500","500-1000","1,000-10,000","10,000-50,000"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-410a has a GWP of 2088, which means it has 2088 times more global warming potential than carbon dioxide. 2088 falls in between 1000 and 10,000."},{"id":"core-086","group":"core","question":"R-410a is the same as:","choices":["CFC-410b","HFC-410b","HFC-410a","HFO-410a"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-410a is an HFC. So it is the same as HFC-410a."},{"id":"core-088","group":"core","question":"The GWP of R-290 is greater than which of the following? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-410a","R-134a","R-22","None of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"R-290 is greater than none of these refrigerants. Recall that R-290 is propane, which is a hydrocarbon. We mentioned that hydrocarbons, or HCs, have the lowest GWPs. Answer choices a, b, and c are either HCFC or HFC refrigerants, which have GWPs in the thousands."},{"id":"core-089","group":"core","question":"What is the main safety concern with R-410a?","choices":["None, it's an A1 refrigerant so there are no safety concerns","Toxicity","Blood oxygenation","Asphyxia"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Even though R-410A is non toxic and has low flammability, it can still cause asphyxia. This is the main concern when it comes to handling R-410A."},{"id":"core-090","group":"core","question":"What does the new subclass (2L) describe?","choices":["Alternate highly flammable refrigerants","Refrigerants that are Class 2 and burn slowly","Refrigerants that are Class 2 and take longer to be effective","Refrigerants that are toxic"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The new subclass of refrigerants, called class 2L, are Class 2 refrigerants that burn slowly. Since they are still class 2, they still have low flammability."},{"id":"core-091","group":"core","question":"What is the highest possible ODP for any CFC, HCFC, HFC, or HFO refrigerant?","choices":["0","1","100","Infinite"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The highest possible ODP for these refrigerants is 1 for R-11, a CFC refrigerant. The potential of any refrigerant to deplete the ozone layer is compared to the ODP of R-11 and will be lower."},{"id":"core-092","group":"core","question":"What is the least possible ODP for a refrigerant?","choices":["1","0","100","None"],"answer":1,"explanation":"ms or The highest ODP is 1 for R-11, a CFC. If a refrigerant does not contain chlorine and does not destroy ozone, it has an ozone depletion potential (ODP) of 0."},{"id":"core-093","group":"core","question":"R-441A is a hydrocarbon refrigerant blend (it contains no chlorine or bromine). What is its ozone depletion potential (ODP)?","choices":["0","0.1","0.2","1"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-441A contains no chlorine or bromine, so it does not deplete the ozone layer. Therefore, its ODP is 0."},{"id":"core-094","group":"core","question":"What is the ODP of R-600a?","choices":["1","0","0.5","0.25"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-600a is isobutane, which is a natural refrigerant. Since natural refrigerants do not contain chlorine, they do not deplete the ozone layer. So their ODP is 0."},{"id":"core-095","group":"core","question":"Which refrigerant class is defined as having low flammability (not zero flammability)?","choices":["Class 1","Class 2","Class 3","Class A"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Class 2 refers to refrigerants with low flammability. Class 1 has no flammability, and Class 3 has high flammability."},{"id":"core-096","group":"core","question":"Which of the following classes refers to a refrigerant that is not flammable at all?","choices":["Class 1","Class 2","Class 3","Class A"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Class 1 is assigned to non-flammable refrigerants."},{"id":"core-097","group":"core","question":"Which refrigerant safety class letter indicates higher toxicity?","choices":["Class 1","Class 3","Class A","Class B"],"answer":3,"explanation":"In refrigerant safety classifications, Class B indicates higher toxicity."},{"id":"core-098","group":"core","question":"Which of the following classes refers to a refrigerant with low toxicity?","choices":["Class 1","Class 3","Class A","Class B"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Class B is high toxicity as we said for the previous question, so class A is low toxicity."},{"id":"core-099","group":"core","question":"3 eset Which gas is used as a reference for measuring GWP?","choices":["CFCs","HCFCs","Ozone","Carbon dioxide"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Carbon dioxide is used as a reference in measuring global warming potential (GWP)."},{"id":"core-100","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are CFCs? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-12","R-1234yf","R-134a","R-11"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-11 and R-12 are CFC refrigerants. R-1234yf is an HFO, and R-134a is an HFC."},{"id":"core-101","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are HCFCs that are seen in most refrigeration systems today?","choices":["R-22","R-123","R-124","R-231"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-22 is the HCFC refrigerant most commonly still seen in refrigeration systems today."},{"id":"core-102","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are HCFCs? (Choose all that apply)","choices":["R-22","R-123 C: R-124","R-211"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-22, R-123, and R-124 are all HCFC refrigerants."},{"id":"core-103","group":"core","question":"Which of the following refrigerants are HFCs? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-134a","R-32","R-12","R-22"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-134a and R-32 are both HFC refrigerants."},{"id":"core-104","group":"core","question":"Why are HFCs still considered harmful to the environment?","choices":["Because they deplete the ozone layer","Because they cause cancer","Because they increase global warming","Because they are harmful to plants"],"answer":2,"explanation":"HFCs are harmful to the environment because they contribute to global warming."},{"id":"core-105","group":"core","question":"What is the chemical name for the HFO refrigerant R-1 234yf commonly used in HVAC systems?","choices":["Trifluoroethane","Tetrafluoropropene","Dichlorofluoromethane","Pentafluoropropane"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-1234yf is also called tetrafluoropropene, a hydrofluoroolefin refrigerant."},{"id":"core-106","group":"core","question":"Which of the following statements about carbon dioxide is true? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Carbon dioxide has a GWP of 1","Carbon dioxide has a GWP of 0","Carbon dioxide has an ODP of 0","Carbon dioxide has an ODP of 1"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Carbon dioxide has a GWP of 1. GWP is a comparison of how much energy a gas absorbs over 100 years, compared to carbon dioxide. Carbon dioxide has an ODP of 0. because it does not contain chlorine so it does not destroy ozone. You have correctly selected 1."},{"id":"core-107","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are natural refrigerants? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-600a","HC-600a","R-134a","R-22"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-600a and HC-600a are both names for isobutane, which is a hydrocarbon refrigerant."},{"id":"core-108","group":"core","question":"Which of the following is NOT a natural refrigerant?","choices":["R-717","R-744","R-130","R-290"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-130 is NOT a natural refrigerant. R-717 is ammonia.R-744 is carbon dioxide.R-290 is propane, a hydrocarbon refrigerant. These three are considered natural refrigerants."},{"id":"core-109","group":"core","question":"Which of the following refrigerants do not destroy the ozone layer? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-1234yf","R-744","R-11","R-22"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-1234yf (HFO) and R-744 (CO,) do not contain chlorine and therefore have an ODP of 0, meaning they do not destroy the ozone layer. R-11 (CFC) and R-22 (HCFC) contain chlorine and have an ODP greater than O, so they do deplete the ozone layer."},{"id":"core-110","group":"core","question":"Which safety classification of refrigerants is most dangerous to use?","choices":["B3","B2L","A2"],"answer":0,"explanation":"B3 refrigerants have high toxicity and high flammability, making them the most dangerous to use. Recall that class B refrigerants have high toxicity and class 3 refrigerants are highly flammable."},{"id":"core-111","group":"core","question":"tre A contractor must choose a refrigerant class for use in an occupied classroom where the lowest combined toxicity and flammability risk is required under ASHRAE Standard 34. Which classification is the best fit?","choices":["B3","A2L","A3","A1"],"answer":3,"explanation":"In ASHRAE 34, the letter indicates toxicity (A = lower, B = higher) and the number indicates flammability (1 = no flame propagation, 2/2L = low, 3 = high). A1 refrigerant is considered the safest due to its low toxicity and non-flammability."},{"id":"core-112","group":"core","question":"A technician is sorting old cylinders by their impact on ozone before disposal. Which type should be flagged as most harmful to the ozone layer?","choices":["HFOs","UFOs","HCFCs","CFCs"],"answer":3,"explanation":"CFCs have the highest ozone depletion potential of all the types of refrigerants because of the three chlorine atoms they contain."},{"id":"core-113","group":"core","question":"Which of the following refrigerants have little to no impact on the ozone layer? (Select all that apply)","choices":["CFCs","HCFCs","HFCs","HFOs"],"answer":2,"explanation":"HFCs and HFOs are non-ozone depleting since they do not have chlorine atoms. They both have an ODP of 0. But CFCs and HCFCs, contain chlorine atoms. So they are the most ozone-depleting. You have correctly selected 1."},{"id":"core-114","group":"core","question":"Which types of refrigerants have the lowest GWPs? (Select two)","choices":["CFCs","HFCs","HFOs","HCs"],"answer":2,"explanation":"HFOs and HCs have the lowest GWPs."},{"id":"core-115","group":"core","question":"Ammonia is safe to use because it is a natural refrigerant.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Ammonia (R-717) is a B2 refrigerant. This means it is toxic, so it is not completely safe to use just because itis a natural refrigerant."},{"id":"core-116","group":"core","question":"GWP measures how much heat a greenhouse gas traps in the atmosphere over 100 years compared to carbon monoxide.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. GWP is a measure of how much heat a greenhouse gas traps in the atmosphere over 100 years compared to carbon dioxide (CO,), NOT carbon monoxide (CO)."},{"id":"core-117","group":"core","question":"If agas has a GWP of 50, it means it has 50 times less global warming potential than carbon dioxide.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. A GWP of 50 means the gas has fifty times more global warming potential than carbon dioxide. It means that this gas will retain fifty times the amount of energy in the atmosphere as carbon dioxide over a hundred years."},{"id":"core-118","group":"core","question":"R-410A is an A1 refrigerant. It has low toxicity and is non-flammable under normal operating conditions, making it one of the safer refrigerants to use.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-410A is classified as an A1 refrigerant, meaning it has low toxicity and no flame propagation under normal operating conditions."},{"id":"core-119","group":"core","question":"Cole The GWPs of HFOs and HCs are close to those of HCFCs.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. The GWP of HFOs and HCs is in the single digits, while that of HCFCs is in the thousands."},{"id":"core-120","group":"core","question":"The lowest number for an ozone depletion potential (ODP) is 1.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. The highest ODP is 1 for R-11, a CFC refrigerant. The potential of any refrigerant to deplete the ozone layer is compared to the ODP of R-11 and will be lower."},{"id":"core-121","group":"core","question":"What is temperature glide?","choices":["The difference between the bubble and dew point","The difference between the boiling point of R-22 and the replacement","When temperature changes in a refrigerant","None of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Temperature glide refers to the difference between the bubble and dew point temperatures of a refrigerant blend during phase change."},{"id":"core-122","group":"core","question":"What is bubble point?","choices":["The temperature at which the first refrigerant in a blend turns to liquid","The temperature at which the first refrigerant in a blend turns to vapor","The temperature at which the last refrigerant in a blend turns to vapor","The same as the boiling point"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The bubble point is the temperature at which the first refrigerant in a blend turns to vapor."},{"id":"core-123","group":"core","question":"What is the definition of dew point for a refrigerant blend?","choices":["The temperature at which the last liquid droplet evaporates into vapor","The temperature at which the first drop of liquid forms from vapor","The temperature at which the first bubble of vapor forms from liquid","The average temperature between liquid and vapor states eG:"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Dew point is the temperature at which the first drop of liquid begins to form as a vapor refrigerant blend starts condensing."},{"id":"core-124","group":"core","question":"A manufacturer lists a refrigerant mixture with R-32 (23%), R-1 72) (25%), and R-134a (52%). How is this blend classified?","choices":["Binary blend","Ternary blend","Azeotrope of R-32/R-125","Single-component HFC"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A blend that contains three refrigerants is a ternary blend. For example, R-407c is a ternary blend of three HFC refrigerants: 23% R-32, 25% R-125, and 52% R-134a."},{"id":"core-125","group":"core","question":"Which of the following is considered retrofitting?","choices":["AnEPA approved process to make DIY refrigerant blends","Replacing a system that used HCFC refrigerants","Replacing HCFC refrigerants with other refrigerants","Modifying components of the system to use anew"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Retrofitting is making changes to an existing system in order to use a new refrigerant in it. It is not replacing the system, just modifying it."},{"id":"core-126","group":"core","question":"Which of the following are reasons to not mix your own refrigerants?","choices":["It is illegal","It can cause equipment failure","The resulting mix has unpredictable temperatures","All of the above"],"answer":3,"explanation":"0 Osos All of these are reasons why technicians cannot mix their own refrigerants."},{"id":"core-127","group":"core","question":"lf a refrigerant has a drop-in replacement, then no retrofit is needed.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. A drop-in replacement has the same exact properties as the original refrigerant. With drop-in refrigerants, no retrofit is needed."},{"id":"core-128","group":"core","question":"In a zeotropic blend, all refrigerants have the same boiling point.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. In an azeotropic blend, all refrigerants have the same boiling point."},{"id":"core-129","group":"core","question":"R-407c is an azeotropic blend.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. R-407c is a zeotropic blend."},{"id":"core-130","group":"core","question":"Refrigerant blends need to be charged as a liquid.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Refrigerant blends need to be charged as a liquid because of fractionation. Charging as a liquid ensures an even sample of the blend."},{"id":"core-131","group":"core","question":"Refrigerant blends take on the ASHRAE number of the main refrigerant in the blend.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Refrigerant blends have their own ASHRAE numbers. These numbers are different from the ASHRAE numbers of the refrigerants that make up the blend."},{"id":"core-132","group":"core","question":"Technicians can make their own EPA-approved refrigerant blends.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Technicians cannot make their own blends."},{"id":"core-133","group":"core","question":"There are no drop-in replacements for R-22 refrigerant.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. There are indeed no direct drop-in replacements for R-22. While there are alternatives available, they may require system modifications to ensure compatibility and efficiency."},{"id":"core-134","group":"core","question":"There are no retrofit refrigerants for R-22.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. There are several retrofit refrigerants available for replacing R-22. Some of the widely recognized retrofit refrigerants for R-22 include: R-453A (RS-44b), R-427A (Forane-427A), R-438A (Freon-MO99Q), R-407C (Freon-407C), R-434A (RS-45), and, R-442A (RS-50)."},{"id":"core-135","group":"core","question":"Alkylbenzene (AB) oil is used for systems with which of the following refrigerants? (Select all that apply)","choices":["CFC","HCFC","HCFC blends","HFC"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Alkylbenzene is used with systems that contain CFCs and HCFCs. This includes systems that contain blends with HCFCs."},{"id":"core-136","group":"core","question":"A bottle of hygroscopic refrigerant oil is left uncapped and then used in a system. What problem is most likely to show up first?","choices":["Viscosity drop causing pump cavitation","Water absorption causing ice blockages","Spontaneous ignition at room temperature","Complete loss of miscibility with refrigerant"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Hygroscopic oils attract and retain moisture. The absorbed water can freeze and obstruct piping, performance and flow."},{"id":"core-137","group":"core","question":"lf we are retrofitting a system to use R-134a, which oil do we need to use?","choices":["Alkylbenzene (AB)","Polyolester (POE)","Mineral Oil (MO)","None of the above"],"answer":1,"explanation":"We need to use polyester oil (POE) with all HFC refrigerant applications. Since R-134 a is an HFC refrigerant, we need to use POE."},{"id":"core-138","group":"core","question":"Oe R-1234yf is not miscible with any refrigerant oils.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. R-1234yf is an HFO refrigerant. HFO refrigerants can be used with POE oils, meaning that HFOs are miscible with POE oils. So R-1234yf is miscible in POE oils."},{"id":"core-139","group":"core","question":"Alkylbenzene (AB) oil is miscible in HCFC refrigerants.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Alkylbenzene is used with systems that contain HCFC, This means it has to be miscible with HCFC refrigerants."},{"id":"core-140","group":"core","question":"vole An ideal oil is best at handling only high temperatures and high pressures.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Oils need to handle all pressures and temperatures in the system. This includes the maximum and minimum of all pressures and temperatures."},{"id":"core-141","group":"core","question":"An ideal oil is readily miscible with the refrigerant in the system.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Oils need to be miscible with the refrigerant at all operating temperatures to ensure efficient heat transfer and reduce the risk of compressor damage."},{"id":"core-142","group":"core","question":"An oil is suitable for use in an enclosed system as long as it is non- flammable only at startup and shutdown temperatures.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. An oil used in an enclosed system must be non-flammable at startup and shutdown temperatures. Being non-flammable only at selected temperatures is not sufficient for safe use."},{"id":"core-143","group":"core","question":"ae Hydrolysis is when refrigerant oils break down in the presence of water.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. This is what hydrolysis is. Oils can break down into acids in the presence of water. This can damage the system equipment."},{"id":"core-144","group":"core","question":"Polyolester oils are great because they can mix with a lot of other oils.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Polyester oils cannot be mixed with any other oils."},{"id":"core-145","group":"core","question":"A supplier is loading refrigerant cylinders for transport to a reclaimer. To meet transport rules, how must the cylinders be arranged?","choices":["Horizontal with chocks under both ends","Valve-down orientation, loosely packed","Upright and secured against tipping","Laid flat but strapped at the middle"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When shipping refrigerants, we always use recovery cylinders and place them upright, securing them in place to prevent tipping.."},{"id":"core-146","group":"core","question":"When shipping refrigerants in hazard class 2.2, what information needs to be on the shipping paper?","choices":["Number of molecules in the cylinder","Number of times the refrigerant has been used","Number of refrigerants in the cylinder","Number of cylinders of each gas"],"answer":3,"explanation":"When shipping refrigerants that are classified as hazard class 2.2, the shipping papers must indicate the number of cylinders of each gas."},{"id":"core-147","group":"core","question":"When sending used refrigerants to be reclaimed, you must use disposable refrigerant cylinders.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. When transporting used refrigerants to be reclaimed, we should only use refillable recovery cylinders. We should not use disposable refrigerant cylinders for sending used refrigerant to be reclaimed."}],"type1":[{"id":"type1-001","group":"type1","question":"A near-azeotropic refrigerant blend typically has:","choices":["A single saturation pressure and temperature with no glide","One high saturation pressure value","Separate bubble-point and dew-point values that are close together","Separate bubble-point and dew-point values with a large difference"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Near-azeotropic blends have bubble-point and dew-point values that are very close together, resulting in a small temperature glide."},{"id":"type1-002","group":"type1","question":"A zeotropic blend will contain:","choices":["One saturation pressure value","One high saturation pressure value","Two saturation pressure values that are close","Two saturation pressure values that have a big difference"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Zeotropic blends have a larger difference between their saturation pressures because their components have different boiling points."},{"id":"type1-003","group":"type1","question":"What is the primary purpose of an access fitting?","choices":["To provide a service connection point for accessing a sealed refrigeration system","To permanently stop refrigerant leaks","To replace the compressor","To increase system pressure"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Access fittings provide a service connection that allows technicians to access a sealed refrigeration system for testing, refrigerant recovery, charging, or other service procedures."},{"id":"type1-004","group":"type1","question":"Defrost heaters in frost-free refrigerators can help with which of the following? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Melt frost buildup on the evaporator coil","Increase refrigerant recovery speed by warming the system","Operate in all Type I appliances","Eliminate the need for refrigerant recovery equipment"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Defrost heaters melt frost buildup on evaporator coils and can also help speed refrigerant recovery by warming the system."},{"id":"type1-005","group":"type1","question":"If the compressor is not working and we are performing passive recovery, we need to take steps to do what?","choices":["Recover at least 80% of charge indicated on appliance nameplate","Vacate the area","Ventilate the working space","Release trapped refrigerant from the compressor oil"],"answer":0,"explanation":"If the compressor is not working, there is likely refrigerant trapped in the compressor oil. We need to take measures to release the trapped refrigerant so we can recover it appropriately under EPA Section 608 regulations."},{"id":"type1-006","group":"type1","question":"If the pressure of the system is found to be 0 psig, can we recover refrigerant from the system?","choices":["Yes","No","It depends on how much refrigerant is left","It depends on the type of refrigerant"],"answer":0,"explanation":"A system at 0 psig may still contain refrigerant, so recovery should still be done."},{"id":"type1-007","group":"type1","question":"If the pressure reading and expected pressure are far apart, which of the following are possibly contained in the refrigerant?","choices":["Air","Water vapor","Nitrogen","All of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"If the pressure reading is not close to the expected pressure, it indicates the presence of non-condensables in the refrigerant. Remember that water vapor and nitrogen are examples of non-condensables."},{"id":"type1-008","group":"type1","question":"A sealed household refrigerator has a working compressor and a blocked capillary tube. To recover the charge, what access setup is required?","choices":["One access valve on the high side only","Two access valves, one on each side","No access valves; pull through service port","One access valve on the low side only"],"answer":0,"explanation":"With a working compressor and a fully restricted cap tube, recovery requires one access valve on the high side of the sealed system."},{"id":"type1-009","group":"type1","question":"Solderless piercing valves:","choices":["Tend to leak over time","Are for permanent use","Should not be left on the appliance after service","Both (A) and (C)"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Solderless piercing valves are generally used to access refrigerant during service and should not be left on the appliance afterward because they tend to leak over time. If we expect to leave the piercing valve on the appliance, we should use a solder-type piercing valve instead."},{"id":"type1-010","group":"type1","question":"What does system-dependent recovery mean?","choices":["Removes only vapor","Uses separate recovery unit","Requires pump-down","Uses appliance compressor"],"answer":3,"explanation":"System-dependent recovery relies on the system's compressor."},{"id":"type1-011","group":"type1","question":"We can use a known refrigerant's PT chart to see if there are non- condensables in the refrigerant.","choices":["Always true","Only true if we can measure the refrigerant's temperature","Only true if we can measure the refrigerant's pressure","Only true if we can measure both the pressure and temperature"],"answer":3,"explanation":"We can only use the PT chart when we can measure a known refrigerant's pressure and temperature, and compare those values to its PT chart to see if they match up."},{"id":"type1-012","group":"type1","question":"According to the PT chart below, what is the approximate pressure of a storage container of R-22 stored at 75°F? Assume there are no impurities. PT Chart","choices":["121 psig","126 psig","132 psig","144 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"According to the PT chart, R-22 at 75°F corresponds to approximately 132 psig."},{"id":"type1-013","group":"type1","question":"According to the PT chart below, what is the approximate pressure of a storage container of R-404A stored at 60°F? Assume there are no impurities. PT Chart Temperature (°F)|Pressure (PSIG) 50°F 105.5 psig 60°F 125.8 psig 70°F 148.1 psig","choices":["105.5 psig","115.8 psig","125.8 psig","148.1 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"According to the P-T chart values provided, R-404A has a saturation pressure of approximately 125.8 PSIG at 60°F."},{"id":"type1-014","group":"type1","question":"What actions are appropriate and safe to recover refrigerant from a system when the compressor is not working? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Use an approved recovery machine and a suitable recovery cylinder","Tap the compressor to \"free it\" and make recovery easier","Heating the system with an open flame (for example, a match)","If the procedure allows it, apply controlled heat using an approved heating blanket (no open flame)"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Use an approved recovery equipment (no open flame). Open flames should not be used, nor should components be \"struck\" as a method of recovery."},{"id":"type1-015","group":"type1","question":"When performing active recovery and the compressor is working, we must recover to what levels?","choices":["90% of the refrigerant charge","4-inch vacuum","Both (a) and (b)","Either (a) or (b)"],"answer":3,"explanation":"If the compressor is working and we are performing an active recovery, we must either recover 90% of the charge, or recover up to a 4-inch vacuum."},{"id":"type1-016","group":"type1","question":"Which method of monitoring fill level is the most accurate?","choices":["Gross cylinder weight","Mechanical float device","Electronic shut-off device","None of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The most accurate method of monitoring fill level uses the gross cylinder weight to see how much refrigerant has been charged."},{"id":"type1-017","group":"type1","question":"Which methods are approved by the EPA to monitor fill level of recovery cylinders?","choices":["Mechanical/Internal float devices","Electronic shut-off devices","Gross cylinder weight","All of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"All these are acceptable methods of monitoring the fill level for recovery cylinders, according to the EPA."},{"id":"type1-018","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following are types of low loss fittings? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Solder type low loss fittings","Manual low loss fittings","Automatic low loss fittings","Hybrid low loss fittings"],"answer":1,"explanation":"There are two types of low-loss fittings: Manual low-loss fittings and automatic low-loss fittings."},{"id":"type1-019","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following are needed to check for non-condensables in a system? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Refrigerant pressure","Humidity","Refrigerant type","Refrigerant weight"],"answer":0,"explanation":"To check for non-condensables, you need both the refrigerant pressure and the refrigerant type. Pressure alone isn't enough; you must compare it to the expected pressure for that specific refrigerant to identify abnormal conditions."},{"id":"type1-020","group":"type1","question":"You are servicing an appliance that contains R-134a. Which of the following can you use to recover the refrigerant?","choices":["A recovery cylinder used for HCFC-22","A recovery cylinder used for HFC-134a","A disposable cylinder used for R-134a","A disposable cylinder used for R-22"],"answer":1,"explanation":"We must use recovery cylinders to recover refrigerant. We cannot use disposable cylinders to recover refrigerant. We also need to make sure that the recovery cylinder is used for the same refrigerant contained in the appliance we are recovering from. And since R-134a is the same as HFC-134a, the correct answer would be (B)."},{"id":"type1-021","group":"type1","question":"We need separate recovery cylinders for each class of refrigerants (e.g. HCFCs). For example, we cannot use the same cylinders to recover CFC and HCFC refrigerants. But we can use the same cylinder to recover different HCFC refrigerants.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. All different refrigerants need to be recovered in separate containers. R-32 and R-134a are both HFC refrigerants, but they would need to be recovered in separate cylinders because they are different refrigerants."},{"id":"type1-022","group":"type1","question":"An active recovery machine is required for all systems. Passive recovery is a thing of the past.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Active recovery using a recovery device is only necessary for appliances with 15 lbs of refrigerant or more. Active recovery machines are not required for appliances with less than 15 lbs of refrigerant."},{"id":"type1-023","group":"type1","question":"For both active recovery and passive recovery, we must recover 80% of the appliance charge if the compressor is not working.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. The method of recovery is irrelevant if the compressor is not working. We need to recover 80% of the appliance charge if the compressor is not working."},{"id":"type1-024","group":"type1","question":"If a refrigerant's pressure readings are not stable, we can use its temperature readings to compare to its PT chart to check for non- condensables.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"For a known refrigerant, both its pressure and temperature must be stable for us to compare them to the PT chart value when checking for non-condensables."},{"id":"type1-025","group":"type1","question":"Installing both high and low side access valves will increase recovery","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. Installing both high and low-side access valves will decrease recovery time."},{"id":"type1-026","group":"type1","question":"Low loss fittings are not only required during refrigerant recovery from appliances containing ODS and their substitutes, but also in other situations such as routine service and pressure checking.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Low-loss fittings are required to minimize refrigerant release during recovery as well as during routine service and pressure checking. Therefore, the statement is true"},{"id":"type1-027","group":"type1","question":"Low loss fittings are required for servicing appliances containing CFCs, HCFCs, and HFCs because of the Venting Prohibition.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. Low-loss fittings prevent us from accidentally releasing ODS and their substitutes into the atmosphere. They are required because of the Venting Prohibition, which makes it illegal to release harmful refrigerants into the air."},{"id":"type1-028","group":"type1","question":"We generally want to leak test access fittings after refrigerant recovery to make sure it does not have leaks for the next service. This is to save us time from leak testing the access fitting the next time around.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. We need to leak test access fittings before Starting the process of refrigerant recovery, not after completing one."},{"id":"type1-029","group":"type1","question":"When the compressor is not working and we are performing passive recovery, we need to access the system from both the high and low side.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This statement is true. When it comes to passive recovery, the process depends on the pressure of the compressor. If it's not working, we need to access both the high and low sides of the system to recover as much refrigerant as possible."},{"id":"type1-030","group":"type1","question":"If a recovery device cannot achieve a 4-inch vacuum, which one of the following does it have to be able to do in order to be used with Type I small appliances? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Recover 80% of refrigerant with a working compressor","Recover 80% of refrigerant with a non-working compressor","Recover 90% of refrigerant with a working compressor","Recover 90% of refrigerant with a non-working compressor"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A recovery device must be able to achieve a 4-inch vacuum or recover 80% of refrigerant with a non-working compressor and 90% of refrigerant with a working compressor."},{"id":"type1-031","group":"type1","question":"If the oil is contaminated, what do we have to do?","choices":["Flush the system","Flush the compressor","Flush the recovery device","All of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"If the oil is contaminated, we need to flush the entire system. Even though the burnout occurred in the compressor, the contaminated oil could be present in other components."},{"id":"type1-032","group":"type1","question":"Non-condensables would [blank] the pressure on the high side of an active recovery device.","choices":["Increase","Decrease","Have no effect on"],"answer":0,"explanation":"If non-condensables are present, the pressure on the high side of an active recovery device would increase."},{"id":"type1-033","group":"type1","question":"Recovery devices are tested and certified by:","choices":["AHRI only","ASHRAE only","Both AHRI and UL","AHRI, UL, and the EPA"],"answer":2,"explanation":"AHRI and UL are the only two organizations approved by the EPA to certify recovery machines. The EPA may approve the organizations that certify these recovery machines, but it does not test and certify them itself."},{"id":"type1-034","group":"type1","question":"The refrigerant vented off the top of charging cylinders needs to be recovered if it is:","choices":["An ozone depleting substance like HCFC","An HFC","A non-exempt substitute","All of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"All refrigerants subject to the Venting Prohibition need to be recovered when vented off the top of charging cylinders."},{"id":"type1-035","group":"type1","question":"Which piece of equipment should be checked regularly for leaks due to its high risk of venting refrigerant?","choices":["Recovery device","Recovery vacuum pump","Access fittings","All of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"We need to check recovery devices regularly for leaks because they have the highest probability of venting refrigerant. It is not necessary to check vacuum pumps for leaks because they only vent non-condensable into the atmosphere. Access fittings need to be leak tested before use, not as part of a regular maintenance routine."},{"id":"type1-036","group":"type1","question":"When the system pressure is found to be 0 psig, what does this indicate?","choices":["The appliance is completely free of refrigerant","There may be only a small amount of refrigerant remaining in the appliance","No additional refrigerant can be recovered","The system has definitely developed a leak"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A pressure reading of 0 psig does not guarantee that all refrigerant has been removed, nor does it prove that a leak has occurred. Some refrigerant may still remain in the appliance even when the gauge reads 0 psig."},{"id":"type1-037","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following indicates a compressor burnout in a sealed system?","choices":["A pungent smell","A pungent, sweet smell","A pungent taste","All of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"A pungent smell usually indicates a compressor burnout."},{"id":"type1-038","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following statements is true for small appliances?","choices":["The EPA requires repair of all leaks above 80% of the leak rate","The EPA does not require repair of leaking small appliances","The AHRI Standard 740 requires repair of leaks","You should not repair leaking small appliances"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The EPA leak repair requirements apply to equipment with a full charge of 50 pounds or more; small appliances are generally excluded from this requirement."},{"id":"type1-039","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following methods can remove non-condensable gases from a refrigeration system?","choices":["Using a filter drier","Flushing the system","Evacuating the system using a vacuum pump","Charging the system with refrigerant"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Filter driers and flushing help remove moisture or contaminants, but they do not remove non-condensable gases from the system."},{"id":"type1-040","group":"type1","question":"A recovery device has to achieve a 4-inch vacuum in all circumstances.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"If the recovery device cannot achieve a 4-inch vacuum, it has to either recover 80% of the refrigerant in a system with a non-working compressor, or 90% of the refrigerant in a system with a working compressor."},{"id":"type1-041","group":"type1","question":"All recovery devices need to be tested according to AHRI Standard 740.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This statement is false. The AHRI Standard 740 is a set of guidelines that lists the requirements for recovery devices. It is not a place where the devices are tested."},{"id":"type1-042","group":"type1","question":"At high temperatures, what do CFCs and HCFCs decompose to?","choices":["Hydrochloric and hydrofluoric acids","Hydrocarbon and hydrofluorocarbons","Chloric and fluoric acids","All of these"],"answer":0,"explanation":"At high temperatures, CFCs and HCFCs decompose into hydrochloric acids and hydrofluoric acids."},{"id":"type1-043","group":"type1","question":"What can happen when CFCs or HCFCs are burned?","choices":["They can create toxic vapors that are harmful to inhale","They can produce phosgene gas","They can release dangerous byproducts","All of the above"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Burning CFCs or HCFCs can create toxic vapors, including phosgene gas, and release dangerous byproducts into the air."},{"id":"type1-044","group":"type1","question":"If refrigerant has been released, what is the first thing you should do?","choices":["Locate an exit","Locate a self-contained breathing apparatus","Locate a specially contained breathing apparatus","Locate the leak to stop the fill of dangerous refrigerant"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The first thing we should do if there is a leak is to locate a self- contained breathing apparatus (SCBA). Preserving life is the priority."},{"id":"type1-045","group":"type1","question":"If a self-contained breathing apparatus cannot be found, what should be done?","choices":["Continue working carefully.","Vacate the area and ventilate it if safe to do so.","Wait until the smell clears.","Search longer for the SCBA."],"answer":1,"explanation":"If an SCBA is not available, leave the area to avoid danger and ventilate it if it is safe to do so."},{"id":"type1-046","group":"type1","question":"Safety markings used in appliances with hydrocarbon refrigerants are:","choices":["Applied by technicians to warn other technicians","Permanently made on the equipment during manufacturing","Have to be put on equipment permanently by technicians","All of these"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Permanent markings are made on required components during manufacture. Technicians just need to be aware of where they are."},{"id":"type1-047","group":"type1","question":"Why must technicians treat refrigerant cylinders as potential explosion hazards?","choices":["The steel shell reacts with moisture to create hydrogen","Cylinders absorb room heat, which weakens the shell","Valves always leak after transport, raising pressure","They are stored under pressure and can rupture violently"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Refrigerants are stored in pressurized cylinders, so there is a real risk of explosion if pressure spikes or the vessel is compromised."},{"id":"type1-048","group":"type1","question":"What piece of equipment is needed on nitrogen tanks when using them to service an appliance?","choices":["Refrigerant thermometer","Pressure regulator","Manual gauge","All of these"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Pressure regulators or relief valves are necessary when using nitrogen tanks to service an appliance. They prevent excessive pressure build- ups that can lead to explosions."},{"id":"type1-049","group":"type1","question":"When do we need to use safety eyewear and butyl-lined gloves?","choices":["When testing the quality of refrigerant","When moving refrigerant cylinders","When connecting and disconnecting hoses Vv","When taring the refrigerant scale"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When connecting and disconnecting hoses, we are at risk of coming into direct contact with refrigerant. This is why we need to wear safety eyewear and butyl lined gloves."},{"id":"type1-050","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following are areas that do not need to be marked when it comes to appliances that contain HCs?","choices":["Outside the refrigerator","Evaporators","Exposed tubing","Inside refrigerator door"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Permanent markings are needed in all of these areas except for inside the refrigerator door. The purpose of these markings is to help the technician identify risk areas."},{"id":"type1-051","group":"type1","question":"According to EPA 608 retrofit guidelines, which refrigerant is approved for retrofitting certain low-temperature R-22 systems, such as household freezers, when proper oil changes and system modifications are performed?","choices":["R-12","R-600a","R-407A","None of these"],"answer":2,"explanation":"This is incorrect. While refrigerants like R-600a are commonly used in modern household freezers, EPA retrofit guidance identifies R-407A as an approved option for retrofitting certain low-temperature R-22 systems when proper modifications are made."},{"id":"type1-052","group":"type1","question":"If we find refrigerant that is mixed, what should we do?","choices":["Destroy it","Send it to the EPA to be reclaimed","Send it to SkillCat to be reclaimed","Send it to a certified reclaiming facility to be reclaimed"],"answer":3,"explanation":"If refrigerant is found to be mixed, it must be sent to a reclaimer. Reclaiming of refrigerant can only be done by a certified reclaiming facility."},{"id":"type1-053","group":"type1","question":"If we use nitrogen to pressurize a system or blow debris out (after fully recovering the refrigerant in the appliance), we can?","choices":["Recover the nitrogen into the same recovery tank as the refrigerant","Vent the nitrogen","Vent the refrigerant because it's useless","All of these"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The answer is B, the nitrogen can be vented. We cannot recover nitrogen into the same tank as the refrigerant because it would contaminate the refrigerant and make it unusable."},{"id":"type1-054","group":"type1","question":"What is isobutane?","choices":["R-290","An acceptable substitute for all household refrigerators and freezers","An unacceptable substitute for new household refrigerators and freezers","An acceptable substitute for new household refrigerators and freezers"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Isobutane is also known as R-600a, an acceptable substitute in new household refrigerators and freezers under the SNAP program."},{"id":"type1-055","group":"type1","question":"Small appliances include:","choices":["Commercial freezers","Commercial refrigerators","Window AC units","All of these"],"answer":2,"explanation":"On this list, only window AC units are considered small appliances. Commercial freezers and commercial refrigerators are not small appliances. These appliances typically have more than five pounds of refrigerant."},{"id":"type1-056","group":"type1","question":"Up to how many pounds of refrigerant can Type I appliances contain?","choices":["3","5","15","50"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Type I appliances can contain a maximum of five pounds of refrigerant"},{"id":"type1-057","group":"type1","question":"Which statement about hydrocarbon refrigerants is correct under EPA SNAP rules?","choices":["Hydrocarbons are highly flammable","Hydrocarbons may be freely used to retrofit any existing system","Hydrocarbons do not require use conditions","Hydrocarbons are approved for all refrigeration applications"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Hydrocarbons are highly flammable and are only allowed in specific applications under EPA SNAP use conditions."},{"id":"type1-058","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following is not true?","choices":["SNAP lists acceptable substitutes for phased out refrigerants for different categories of end-uses","SNAP is implemented by the EPA","Refrigerants can be classified as unacceptable under SNAP","None of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"All of these are true."},{"id":"type1-059","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following statements is true about refrigerant recovery?","choices":["You can only sell refrigerant that is reclaimed to virgin specifications","Reclaimers can refuse to accept contaminated refrigerant","Reclaimers can charge extra for processing contaminated refrigerant","All of these"],"answer":3,"explanation":"All of these statements are true."},{"id":"type1-060","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following refrigerants is not covered by the sales restriction of Section 608?","choices":["R-717","R-134a","R-22","R-12"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-717 is ammonia, a natural refrigerant, and is therefore exempted from the Section 608 sales restriction. R-22 is an HCFC refrigerant, and R-12 is a CFC refrigerant. Both are covered by the sales restriction. R-134a is an HFC refrigerant. All containers of R-134a greater than 2 lbs are subject to the sales restriction."},{"id":"type1-061","group":"type1","question":"Which of these can be vented? (Select all that apply)","choices":["R-717","R-744","R-728","R-134a"],"answer":0,"explanation":"These three can all be vented because they are exempted from the Venting Prohibition. R-717 is ammonia, R-744 is carbon dioxide, and R-728 is nitrogen. All these are natural refrigerants."},{"id":"type1-062","group":"type1","question":"R-22 is listed as an acceptable substitute under the SNAP program.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-22 is not listed as an acceptable substitute under the SNAP program because it is an ozone-depleting HCFC refrigerant."},{"id":"type1-063","group":"type1","question":"R-404A may still be found in some household refrigerators and freezers.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-404A may still be found in some household refrigerators and freezers, especially in older equipment."},{"id":"type1-064","group":"type1","question":"R-407C can be found in new household refrigerators and freezers.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"We do not expect to see R-407c in new household refrigerators and freezers. However, we may still find them in models that were manufactured before January 2021, which is when the SNAP rule on HFC blends became active."},{"id":"type1-065","group":"type1","question":"For R-22, there are no drop-in substitutes.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The EPA does not recognize any drop-in substitutes for systems that operate on R-22 refrigerant. If we want to use a new refrigerant in an R-22 system, we must first retrofit it."},{"id":"type1-066","group":"type1","question":"Hermetically sealed systems can still lose refrigerant over time.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Hermetically sealed systems are designed to minimize refrigerant leaks, but they can still lose refrigerant over time due to wear, corrosion, vibration, or damage."},{"id":"type1-067","group":"type1","question":"If a dehumidifier has 60 ounces of R-32, it is considered a Type I appliance under Section 608.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Small appliance that contains 5 pounds (80 ounces) or less of refrigerant. Since 60 ounces is less than 80 ounces, and R-32 is an HFC refrigerant covered under Section 608, this dehumidifier qualifies as a Type I appliance."},{"id":"type1-068","group":"type1","question":"If a humidifier has 90 ounces of R-32, it is considered a Type I appliance under Section 608.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"This humidifier is not considered a Type I appliance under Section 608 because 90 ounces is greater than 5 lbs (or 80 0z)."},{"id":"type1-069","group":"type1","question":"If a water cooler has 14 ounces of R-134a, it is considered a Type I appliance under Section 608.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"This water cooler is considered a Type I appliance under Section 608 because 14 ounces is less than 5 lbs (or 80 oz), and R-134a is an HFC refrigerant, which is covered under Section 608."},{"id":"type1-070","group":"type1","question":"If I don't have Section 608 certification, I can buy 3 Lb cans of R-134a.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The small can exemption only covers cans of non-exempt substitute refrigerant up to 2 lbs. Since R-134a is an HFC, it is anon-exempt substitute."},{"id":"type1-071","group":"type1","question":"If we have two HFC refrigerants, we can use the same recovery cylinder because they are the same type of refrigerant.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"We can only recover one type of refrigerant in any given recovery cylinder. Even when they're both HFC refrigerants, they still have different properties."},{"id":"type1-072","group":"type1","question":"Low loss fittings are required for servicing systems containing ODS in order to comply with the Venting Prohibition.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Using low-loss fittings allows us to be compliant with the Venting Prohibition by preventing the loss of ODS. Failure to use low-loss fittings is considered a violation of the Venting Prohibition."},{"id":"type1-073","group":"type1","question":"MVACs are considered Type I appliances under Section 608 but MVAC-like systems are not.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Neither MVACs nor MVAC-like systems are considered Type I systems. These are covered under EPA 609."},{"id":"type1-074","group":"type1","question":"New household refrigerators and freezers containing R-290 can contain 3 lbs of refrigerant.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-290 is a hydrocarbon so it is subject to the use condition that household refrigerators and freezers containing R-290 can only contain up to 2 lbs of the refrigerant."},{"id":"type1-075","group":"type1","question":"Nitrogen can be used to pressurize or blow debris out of a system containing a half charge of refrigerant.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The refrigerant in a system should be fully recovered before using nitrogen to pressurize the system or blow debris out."},{"id":"type1-076","group":"type1","question":"Only refrigerant blends without HFCs are acceptable under the SNAP program.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Refrigerant blends with HFC refrigerants are still acceptable under the SNAP program provided they contain a blend of more than just HFC refrigerants."},{"id":"type1-077","group":"type1","question":"R-450a is an acceptable substitute for use in new household refrigerators and freezers under SNAP. This means new household refrigerators and freezers can be factory charged with R-450a.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"R-450a is an acceptable substitute for factory- charging new household refrigerators and freezers under the SNAP program."},{"id":"type1-078","group":"type1","question":"Section 608 is part of the Clean Air Act.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Section 608 is regulated under the Clean Air Act. All violations of Section 608 are subject to CAA fines and punishments."},{"id":"type1-079","group":"type1","question":"The SNAP program could label refrigerant A as an acceptable substitute for use in a chiller but an unacceptable substitute for vending machines.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The SNAP program looks at a refrigerant's use in a particular end-use or appliance. Just because it is considered an acceptable substitute for one appliance does not make it an acceptable substitute for all appliances."},{"id":"type1-080","group":"type1","question":"Under EPA Section 608 guidelines, trace gases used for leak detection are not considered refrigerants and may be used with small residual amounts of refrigerant remaining in a system during leak testing.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Trace gases used for leak detection are not considered refrigerants under EPA Section 608 guidelines. After most of the refrigerant has been recovered, trace gases may be used with small residual amounts of refrigerant remaining in the system to help locate leaks."},{"id":"type1-081","group":"type1","question":"A system with a total refrigerant charge of exactly 3 lb is classified as Type I.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Type 1 systems can have a maximum of pounds of refrigerant, so they can have any amount of refrigerant less than five pounds."},{"id":"type1-082","group":"type1","question":"QAll Type I small appliances must be charged by the technician before first use.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Type I systems are factory-charged. This means technicians do not need to recharge the appliance. All the refrigerant needed is already contained inside the appliance. Type I appliances can be used straight out of the box."},{"id":"type1-083","group":"type1","question":"We can retrofit an old appliance to operate on 2 lbs of R-600a.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-600a is a hydrocarbon, and under the use conditions, we cannot retrofit old appliances to operate on hydrocarbons because they are highly flammable. Any malfunction of the modified parts will be dangerous and can cause fires or explosions. The 2 Ib maximum charge applies to new appliances only."},{"id":"type1-084","group":"type1","question":"We only have to recover refrigerants before servicing systems containing CFCs and HCFCs.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"We need to recover refrigerants before servicing any system containing CFCs, HCFCs, and their non-exempt substitutes. This includes HFC and HFO refrigerants as well."},{"id":"type1-096","group":"type1","question":"According to the PT chart below, what is the approximate pressure of a storage container of R-22 stored at 75°F? Assume there are no impurities.","choices":["121 psig","126 psig","132 psig","144 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"According to the PT chart, R-22 at 75°F corresponds to approximately 132 psig."},{"id":"type1-097","group":"type1","question":"According to the PT chart below, what is the approximate pressure of a storage container of R-404A stored at 60°F? Assume there are no impurities.","choices":["105.5 psig","115.8 psig","125.8 psig","148.1 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"According to the P-T chart values provided, R-404A has a saturation pressure of approximately 125.8 PSIG at 60°F."},{"id":"type1-103","group":"type1","question":"Which of the following are needed to check for non-condensables ina system? (Select all that apply)","choices":["Refrigerant pressure","Humidity","Refrigerant type","Refrigerant weight"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Checking for non-condensables requires both refrigerant pressure and refrigerant type. Pressure must be interpreted using the correct refrigerant's pressure-temperature relationship. Without both, the reading cannot be evaluated accurately. You have correctly selected 1."},{"id":"type1-109","group":"type1","question":"Installing both high and low side access valves will increase recovery time.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Installing both high and low-side access valves will increase recovery speed, not recovery time. Because it is faster, it will decrease recovery time."},{"id":"type1-112","group":"type1","question":"System dependent recovery captures refrigerant in a pressurized container to keep it fresh.","choices":["True","False"],"answer":1,"explanation":"With system dependent recovery, we use a non-pressurized container to capture the refrigerant."}],"type2":[{"id":"type2-001","group":"type2","question":"After opening a system for service, a technician suspects moisture is present. Which corrective action should be taken to protect the system?","choices":["Purge the condenser to vent vapor G","Drain the oil separator completely","Reduce condenser water flow for longer contact time","Install a correctly sized filter drier"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Use a liquid-line filter drier; it's designed to remove moisture and other contaminants from the refrigerant system."},{"id":"type2-002","group":"type2","question":"Which statement best explains how the compressor heater protects the compressor at start-up?","choices":["It heats the compressor oil to boil off any refrigerant mixed in","It raises discharge pressure so the condenser rejects heat more quickly","It dries the moisture in the receiver to stop rust in the liquid line","It preheats suction gas so the evaporator runs at temperature"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The compressor heater warms the compressor oil. Refrigerant boils off first, so the oil isn't diluted. With full-strength oil, the compressor has proper lubrication at start-up."},{"id":"type2-003","group":"type2","question":"What visual indication might be seen ona moisture-indicating sight glass if moisture is present in a refrigeration system?","choices":["Aclear, unobstructed view through the glass","Acolor change/discoloration of the moisture indicator Vv element in the sight glass","Scratches or cracks appearing on the glass QO . -Onaae","Water dripping from the sight glass"],"answer":1,"explanation":"A moisture-indicating sight glass uses a moisture-sensitive indicator that changes color when moisture is present."},{"id":"type2-004","group":"type2","question":"Before servicing a rooftop unit, where should you verify th official specifications?","choices":["The unit's nameplate","Thecontroller's live display screen","The last technician's service sticker","The color chart on the sight glass"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The nameplate is where the system's manufacturer has listed all specifications for that particular system. Always verify specs on the nameplate before the service."},{"id":"type2-005","group":"type2","question":"Where should a receiver tank be hooked to tap refrigerant in liquid form during service?","choices":["Onthe vapor line, close to the compressor inlet","Onthe suction line, midway to the evaporator","On the liquid line, close to the condenser outlet","On the discharge line, far from the condenser"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A receiver tank connects to the liquid line near the condenser outlet to capture the high-pressure liquid leaving the condenser coils."},{"id":"type2-006","group":"type2","question":"When the suction service valve is back-seated, which port is Cosed?","choices":["Suction line and compressor port","Compressor and gauge port","Compressor port","Gauge port"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Backseating a suction shutoff valve will close the gauge/service port of the valve."},{"id":"type2-007","group":"type2","question":"Which of the following components is located just before the compressor?","choices":["Receiver","Suction Line Accumulator","Condenser coils","TEV"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The'accumulator, also called the suction line accumulator is located just before the compressor and prevents liquid refrigerant from entering it."},{"id":"type2-008","group":"type2","question":"Which of the following refrigerants is not used in Type II systems?","choices":["R-407C","R-407A","R-245fa","R-22"],"answer":2,"explanation":"R-245fa is not a high-pressure refrigerant, so it is not used in Type II systems."},{"id":"type2-009","group":"type2","question":"Which of the following tasks falls within EPA Section 608 Type II work?","choices":["Recover R-134a from an MVAC at an auto service bay","Evacuate a low-pressure R-123 centrifugal chiller","Service an R-410A rooftop unit at a supermarket site","Repair a small window AC with less than 5 lbs of refrigerant"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Type II covers work on high/very high-pressure appliances, which include systems like rooftop units using high- pressure refrigerants such as R-410A."},{"id":"type2-010","group":"type2","question":"A plant chiller sends 52% of its cooling capacity to a chemical process loop and 48% to office HVAC. How is it classified?","choices":["Commercial refrigeration","Industrial process refrigeration","Comfort cooling","Ice making refrigeration"],"answer":1,"explanation":"If an appliance uses more than 50% of its cooling capacity for industrial processes (manufacturing line in this case), it is classified as an industrial process refrigeration system."},{"id":"type2-011","group":"type2","question":"A customer has an IPR system with 2000 pounds of R-22 refrigerant that has exceeded its leak rate threshold. How often is the customer required to perform a leak inspection after repair?","choices":["Every month","Every 3 months","Every 6 months","Once per calendar year"],"answer":1,"explanation":"For an IPR system with more than 500 pounds of refrigerant, it is compulsory to perform a leak inspection every 3 months after repairing the leak."},{"id":"type2-012","group":"type2","question":"A supermarket commercial refrigeration rack with 400 Ib of R-410A refrigerant was repaired for leaks. How often must leak inspections be performed after repair?","choices":["Only if leaks return","Every 3 months","Every 6 months","Once per calendar year"],"answer":3,"explanation":"For a commercial refrigeration system with 50 to 500 pounds of refrigerant, it is compulsory to perform a leak inspection once per calendar year after repairing any leaks."},{"id":"type2-013","group":"type2","question":"Before leak checks on a newly assembled field-piped system, what factor most strongly affects how many leaks you're likely to find?","choices":["The refrigerant blend chosen for the outdoor unit charge.","The ambient humidity on the day of the initial installation.","The cabinet age of the outdoor section in the condenser","The proficiency of the installer who did the brazing and piping work"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The leak count is largely driven by installer skill and workmanship on the field-piped systems."},{"id":"type2-014","group":"type2","question":"On January 10, 2024, an HVAC servicing company disposes of a rooftop unit containing 35 Lb of refrigerant. Until what date must the company retain the disposal records at minimum?","choices":["January 10, 2026","January 10,2027","January 10,2028","January 10,2025"],"answer":1,"explanation":"An HVAC servicing company that disposes of an appliance with a charge between 5 and 50 pounds must keep the records for a minimum period of 3 years. From January 10, 2024, years is January 10, 2027."},{"id":"type2-015","group":"type2","question":"A 60-Ib comfort-cooling unit fails verification after a leak repair. The Owner decides to retire it and replace it with a CO2 (R-744) system, which is exempt from the Venting Prohibition. Under EPA leak-repair rules, the retirement must be completed within:","choices":["24 months","6 months","12 months","18 months"],"answer":3,"explanation":"If a replacement uses a refrigerant exempt from venting prohibitions, the owner or operator has 18 months to retire or retrofit the appliance in question."},{"id":"type2-016","group":"type2","question":"During an audit, a facility with several chillers (each containing more than 50 lbs of ODP refrigerant) is asked for records of leak inspections and both verification tests after repairs. For compliance, the owner and operator must keep these records for at least:","choices":["2 years","3 years","5 years","Life of the appliance"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The owners and operators of regulated appliances containing 50 or more pounds of regulated refrigerant should maintain all records for at least 3 years."},{"id":"type2-017","group":"type2","question":"A grocery store's 120-lb R-22 rack shows an annualized leak rate of 22% in its 2019 log. Under EPA rules for commercial refrigeration with more than 50 Ib, which annual leak-rate threshold triggers the mand atory repair requirement?","choices":["10% annually","20% annually","30% annually","40% annually"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The maximum leak rate set by the EPA for a commercial refrigeration system is 20%. If a commercial refrigeration system has a leak rate higher than 20%, then it must be repaired."},{"id":"type2-018","group":"type2","question":"During a service call on a 60-Ib system, you must verify whether the annual leak rate exceeds the EPA limit before topping off. To do that, you first need the system's full charge. According to EPA rules, which method(s) may be used to determine the full charge?","choices":["Calculations based on power consumption, in kWh","Calculations based on tonnage","Calculations based on component and pipe sizes","Calculations based on the BTU capacity of the system"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The EPA allows the use of calculations based on component and pipe sizes to determine the full charge in the system."},{"id":"type2-019","group":"type2","question":"Which of these methods is the best for pinpointing the exact location of a refrigerant leak?","choices":["Ultrasonic Leak Detector","Soap Bubble Leak Detection Test","Electronic Leak Detection","Leak Sniffing Method"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The best method to test a system for leaks is by using soap bubbles is to pinpoint the exact location of the leaks."},{"id":"type2-020","group":"type2","question":"What is the first step to take to ensure a newly assembled system is leak-free?","choices":["Introduce an initial charge of refrigerant","Pressurize with an inert gas and leak check.","Pressurize with the refrigerant to be used in the system.","Pull a vacuum after adding refrigerant"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Any newly assembled system should first be pressurized with nitrogen to ensure it is leak-free."},{"id":"type2-021","group":"type2","question":"You're pressure-testing an R-407C field-piped system. A trace gas is required to improve electronic detection. Which setup is code-compliant?","choices":["Nitrogen with a trace of R-22","Air with a trace of R-407C","Nitrogen with a trace of R-407C","CO2 only at moderate pressure"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When a trace gas is absolutely necessary, use nitrogen with a small amount of the system's designated refrigerant. In this case, R-407C. This aligns with the code's best practice."},{"id":"type2-022","group":"type2","question":"On a hermetic system with suspected leakage, which visual clue around joints and fittings most strongly suggests a slow, ongoing leak?","choices":["Bright, clean copper with no discoloration","Uniform frost on every exposed surface","Dull oxide layer with no residue present","Darkened dust stuck to a light oil film"],"answer":3,"explanation":"A thin oil film that collects dark dust is a classic sign of a slow refrigerant leak at that location."},{"id":"type2-023","group":"type2","question":"Which of the following installations is Classified as commercial refrigeration under EPA leak-repair rules?","choices":["A supermarket's display-case lineup","A bank's rooftop chiller for offices","A pharma plant brine chiller","An arena ice-rink chiller"],"answer":0,"explanation":"A supermarket's display-case lineup is commercial refrigeration. In contrast, a bank's rooftop chiller for offices is comfort cooling, and a pharma plant's brine chiller is Industrial Process Refrigeration (IPR)."},{"id":"type2-024","group":"type2","question":"Which of the following situations does qualify for an extension of a leak-repair deadline?","choices":["No tech available to visit site","Owner wants to delay repair","Budget approval still pending","Critical part is not available"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Extensions are allowed for specific constraints like documented part unavailability, not for staffing, budget, or convenience."},{"id":"type2-025","group":"type2","question":"Which reading combination most strongly suggests a refrigerant undercharge caused by a leak in a capillary-tube system?","choices":["High suction pressure with low superheat","High suction pressure with high subcooling","Low suction pressure with high superheat","Normal suction pressure with zero superheat"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Low suction pressure combined with high superheat is a common sign of refrigerant undercharge caused by a leak ina capillary-tube system."},{"id":"type2-026","group":"type2","question":"Which set of actions correctly mothballs an appliance under EPA rules?","choices":["Power off the unit and move it to warehouse storage","Isolate the section, shut it down, and evacuate to atmospheric pressure","Close liquid line only; leave suction open; keep it running","Recover to 0 psig, restart, and schedule parts for later"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Proper mothballing requires evacuating to atmospheric pressure, isolating, and temporarily shutting down the equipment."},{"id":"type2-027","group":"type2","question":"In which of the following cases will charging a system that contains 50+ pounds of ozone-depleting refrigerant require you to calculate its leak rate?","choices":["following a retrofit","During the installation of a new appliance","During a qualified seasonal variance","When topping off the system"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The requirement to calculate the leak rate gets triggered when topping off refrigerant in any system containing more than 50 pounds of refrigerant."},{"id":"type2-028","group":"type2","question":"In a refrigeration compressor, which component is most likely to fail and cause leaks after months of inactivity due to hardened rubber seals?","choices":["Pressure relief valve","Rotating shaft seal VS","Discharge service valve","Head gasket"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Rubber seals within the rotating shaft seal often hardens and loses its sealing ability over time."},{"id":"type2-029","group":"type2","question":"When drawing deep vacuums, a hermetic recovery machine will:","choices":["Run faster than other recovery units","Overheat due to reduced flow of refrigerant through the compressor","Cause high compression of recovered refrigerant","Make the oil used in hermetic compressor to become highly viscous"],"answer":1,"explanation":"When drawing a deep vacuum, the hermetic compressors' motor overheats as there is little refrigerant flowing through it to cool it down."},{"id":"type2-030","group":"type2","question":"A technique to speed up the recovery process is:","choices":["Use aplastic recovery tank","Cool the recovery cylinder","Use a four-stage vacuum pump","Heat the recovery cylinder"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Cooling the recovery cylinder reduces the pressure inside it, creating more space inside and reducing the resistance to refrigerant flow. Ultimately, this leads to quicker recovery."},{"id":"type2-031","group":"type2","question":"A technician just finished liquid refrigerant recovery on an appliance. What must be done with the remaining refrigerant vapor to finish the recovery process?","choices":["Pumped into the receiver by running the compressor","Purged slowly to the atmosphere at low pressure","Isolated in the system until pressure equalizes","Recovered through the vapor line using the recovery unit"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Recovery isn't complete until you also remove the vapor. After the liquid recovery is complete, the vapor refrigerant left in the system should also be recovered using the recovery equipment."},{"id":"type2-032","group":"type2","question":"During refrigerant recovery, water from the local municipal water supply is used to cool the:","choices":["Water-cooled chillers","Hermetic recovery unit","Water-cooled recovery unit","Deionized water recovery unit"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Local municipal water is continuously passed over the condenser coils of a water-cooled recovery unit during recovery."},{"id":"type2-033","group":"type2","question":"Recovering refrigerant from a system in the liquid phase will cause the loss of which of the following?","choices":["Water","Oil","Refrigerant","Non-condensables"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Refrigerant oil is mixed with liquid refrigerant in high quantities. During liquid recovery, the oil is recovered along with the refrigerant. This refrigerant oil is lost and can't be filtered back."},{"id":"type2-034","group":"type2","question":"A technician begins recovery on a supermarket parallel rack without closing isolation valves. The recovery stalls even though the machine is on. What system feature is causing this?","choices":["Hot-gas bypass cycling the TXV","Suction accumulator trapping liquid","Shared discharge header equalizing pressure","Crankcase heaters boiling off oil"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A parallel compressor system (parallel rack system) has an open equalization connection. it would be impossible to recover refrigerant without isolating the parallel compressor system. The shared header equalizes pressure."},{"id":"type2-035","group":"type2","question":"Self-sealing connectors and hand valves are used because they:","choices":["Minimize the chance of an explosion","Minimize refrigerant mixing with the refrigerant oil","Minimize refrigerant release when hoses are connected and disconnected","Prevent vapor lock during liquid transfer"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Self-sealing connectors and hand valves are types of low-loss fittings that minimize refrigerant release when connecting and disconnecting hoses."},{"id":"type2-036","group":"type2","question":"Before filling a cylinder with refrigerant, which step must be performed first?","choices":["Purge the cylinder with oxygen","Mix the refrigerant thoroughly","Heat the cylinder","Evacuate the cylinder"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Before transferring refrigerant into an empty cylinder, it should first be evacuated to remove any non-condensable gases that may have seeped into it."},{"id":"type2-037","group":"type2","question":"What must be compieted before connecting a recovery unit to evacuate refrigerant?","choices":["Acid testing the refrigerant.","Flushing the recovery unit using nitrogen.","Replace or top up the recovery unit's oil as needed.","Checking the service valve positions and recovery oil level, when applicable."],"answer":3,"explanation":"While using a recovery unit, a technician should first check the service valve's positions to prevent accidental venting of refrigerant. The oil level in the recovery unit must also be checked before starting the recovery process."},{"id":"type2-038","group":"type2","question":"When servicing an appliance with a receiver/storage tank:","choices":["the compressor discharge valve should be closed","the compressor suction valve should be closed","refrigerant should be pumped down to and isolated in the receiver","agauge pressure of \"0\" psia should be achieved by venting"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When servicing an appliance with a receiver tank, the refrigerant should be pumped down to and isolated in the receiver tank to save time and effort."},{"id":"type2-039","group":"type2","question":"You're servicing a unit with a receiver tank. The receiver outlet sits higher than the condenser outlet. Where should you pull from to recover correctly?","choices":["From the condenser outlet","From the receiver outlet","From the compressor discharge","From the liquid line sight glass"],"answer":0,"explanation":"If the condenser outlet is lower than the receiver tank outlet, the refrigerant is removed from the condenser outlet. If this is not done, refrigerant liquid might be stuck in the condenser coils."},{"id":"type2-040","group":"type2","question":"Under EPA Section 608 recovery requirements, using EPA-certified recovery equipment manufactured on or after Nov 15, 1993, to what level must a high-pressure appliance containing 1000 Ib of R-407C be evacuated before opening the system for a major repair?","choices":["O psig","25mm Hg absolute","10 inches of Hg vacuum","15 inches of Hg vacuum"],"answer":2,"explanation":"For a high-pressure appliance with a full charge of 200 Ib or more, the required evacuation level (post-1993 equipment) is 10 inches of Hg vacuum. (15 inches of Hg vacuum applies to medium-pressure appliances with 200 Ib or more.)"},{"id":"type2-041","group":"type2","question":"A [blank] pressure on the [blank] side can confirm the presence of non-condensable gases in the system.","choices":["lower; suction","higher; suction","lower; discharge","higher; discharge"],"answer":3,"explanation":"We can confirm the presence of non-condensable gases if the discharge side pressure in the refrigeration system is higher."},{"id":"type2-042","group":"type2","question":"How can we charge an 80-pound R407C system with air-cooled components?","choices":["Vapor charge through the suction service valve","Vapor charge through the liquid-line service valve","Liquid charge through the suction service valve","Liquid charge through the liquid-line service valve"],"answer":3,"explanation":"We can use liquid charging in a system that has an air-cooled condenser and evaporator coils. Since these systems do not have. water, there is no risk of ice formation during liquid charging. Liquid charging is always done via the liquid-line service valve."},{"id":"type2-043","group":"type2","question":"Refrigerant has been recovered during the replacement of the evaporator coil in an appliance. After the repairs, the refrigerant:","choices":["can be filled back into the system","can be sold as it is to another equipment owner q","must be reclaimed","must be destroyed"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Any recovered refrigerant can be charged back into the system once the repairs are done."},{"id":"type2-044","group":"type2","question":"Water in an R-410A system may freeze until the pressure rises to about the saturation pressure at 32°F. Approximately what pressure Is that on the PT chart?","choices":["63 psig","90 psig","100 psig","110 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The saturation pressure of R-410A at 32°F is approximately 101 psig. Since the PT chart values must be estimated and 100 psig is the closest answer choice provided, it is the best answer."},{"id":"type2-045","group":"type2","question":"Water present in the system can freeze if:","choices":["Alarge vacuum pump is used for evacuation","A recovery unit is used for evacuation","Thesystem's compressor is used for evacuation","A house vacuum cleaner is used for evacuation"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The system's pressure (and temperature) can reduce very quickly while evacuating with a large vacuum pump. This sudden decrease in temperature can cause the water in the system to freeze and form ice."},{"id":"type2-046","group":"type2","question":"What is the standing pressure of R-410A at 80°F?","choices":["143 psig","180 psig","235 psig","260 psig"],"answer":2,"explanation":"About 235 psig at 80°F."},{"id":"type2-047","group":"type2","question":"At 0 psig pressure, what is the approximate evaporation temperature pf R-134a","choices":["-21°Fahrenheit","-15°Fahrenheit","-6° Fahrenheit","O° Fahrenheit"],"answer":1,"explanation":"On the R-134a P-T chart, O psig corresponds to a saturation temperature of approximately 15°F."},{"id":"type2-048","group":"type2","question":"During the evacuation of a moisture-laden chiller, the vacuum stalls, and frost begins to form in the piping. What action should the technician take to restore flow without adding refrigerant?","choices":["Adda small refrigerant charge to warm the lines, then pull again","Run the compressor to heat the circuit before continuing evacuation","Open the system to room air to equalize pressure and temperature","Break the vacuum with a brief nitrogen sweep, then resume evacuation"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Introducing nitrogen raises pressure and temperature, preventing freezing of the moisture inside the system. After the brief nitrogen sweep, resume evacuation to remove both the nitrogen and the moisture."},{"id":"type2-049","group":"type2","question":"Which units are used to measure a deep vacuum?","choices":["Psig","Psia","Inches of Hg","Microns"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The pressure in a deep vacuum is measured in units called microns."},{"id":"type2-050","group":"type2","question":"A \"major repair\" under EPA's regulations would be:","choices":["Replacing a condenser coil","Replacing a filter-drier","Replacing a condenser fan motor","Replacing a blower fan motor"],"answer":0,"explanation":"EPA defines major repairs as maintenance, service, or repair that involves the removal of the appliance's condenser, evaporator auxiliary heat exchanger coil, or compressor. By this definition, replacing a condenser coil is a \"major repair.\""},{"id":"type2-051","group":"type2","question":"An equipment room has an appliance that uses R717. Under ASHRAE Standard 15, which piece of equipment is not compulsory in the room?","choices":["Fire extinguisher","Refrigerant Detector","Mechanical ventilation system","Mechanical exhaust fans"],"answer":1,"explanation":"For an equipment room with R717 (ammonia) in its systems, a ; refrigerant detector is not needed."},{"id":"type2-052","group":"type2","question":"Oil foaming in a system can be detected in the:","choices":["Condenser","Evaporator","Compressor","Expansion device"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Most refrigerant oil can be found in the compressor of an appliance, so oil foaming is also commonly seen in the compressor. ;"},{"id":"type2-053","group":"type2","question":"A piping sketch shows two pressure relief valves installed one after the other on the same discharge line. What is the correct action?","choices":["Reject the design; relief valves must not be in series","Accept if both valves have the same set pressure","Accept with annual testing and documentation","Accept only on large receivers with high charge"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Pressure relief valves should never be installed in series to the system lines. It doesn't add protection and can cause improper discharge."},{"id":"type2-054","group":"type2","question":"The purpose of isopropyl alcohol is:","choices":["To regulate the pressure during evacuation","Toremove air from the filter drier","Toclean ice and dirt off the sight glass","To vent the refrigerant"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Ice can form on the sight glass at low temperatures, so it should be cleaned using an isopropyl alcohol spray."},{"id":"type2-055","group":"type2","question":"We would takean [blank] if aunithasa compressor burnout, and it is considereda [blank].","choices":["Refrigerant sample; major repair","Air sample; minor repair","Oil sample; major repair","Oil sample; normal repair"],"answer":2,"explanation":"A compressor burnout is a major repair, and an oil sample is taken to detect it. A sample of the oil is taken to check its properties."},{"id":"type2-056","group":"type2","question":"When the [blank] is closed, the reciprocating compressor might get damaged if it is energized.","choices":["Discharge service valve","Suction service valve","Shut-off valve","Thermal expansion valve CE"],"answer":0,"explanation":"When the discharge service valve is closed, the reciprocating compressor might get damaged if it is energized."},{"id":"type2-057","group":"type2","question":"After opening a system to repair a small leak, a technician pulls a deep vacuum and prepares to recharge. Which component must be replaced before charging?","choices":["Filter drier","Sight glass","Liquid receiver","Crankcase heater"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Opening the system introduces air, moisture, and other contaminants that evacuation alone won't remove from the filter drier, The filter drier is a closed component meant to trap air and moisture. So it is best to replace it whenever the system is opened for repairs."}],"type3":[{"id":"type3-001","group":"type3","question":"After the refrigerant leaves the purge unit, where does it go?","choices":["Condenser","Recovery Cylinder","Evaporator","Compressor"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The refrigerant from the purge unit free from air and moisture enters the evaporator through the expansion valve."},{"id":"type3-002","group":"type3","question":"Which classification best describes R-123's toxicity according to ASHRAE safety rating?","choices":["Low toxicity","High toxicity","Medium toxicity","Non-toxic"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-123 is identified as having high toxicity."},{"id":"type3-003","group":"type3","question":"What is the ASHRAE safety rating of R-1233zd?","choices":["B1","B2","A1","A2"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The ASHRAE safety rating of R-1233zd is A1."},{"id":"type3-004","group":"type3","question":"According to the PT chart, what is the normal boiling point of R-123 at atmospheric pressure?","choices":["74.9 °F","82 °F","-41.3 °F","-55.4 °F"],"answer":1,"explanation":"At atmospheric pressure, the normal boiling point of R-123 is approximately 82 °F according to the PT chart."},{"id":"type3-005","group":"type3","question":"What is the pressure of R-123 at 80°F on the PT chart?","choices":["18.1 inches Hg","1.2 inches Hg i","14.7 psia"],"answer":1,"explanation":"On the PT chart, the R-123 value at 80°F is 1.2 inches Hg vacuum."},{"id":"type3-006","group":"type3","question":"While preparing to charge a low-pressure chiller, you check the safety limit for over-pressure protection. The rupture disc is designed to burst at:","choices":["10 psig","15 psig","5psig","20 psig"],"answer":1,"explanation":"For low-pressure refrigeration systems like chillers using R-123 or R-11, the EPA specifies that the rupture disc is set to relieve at 15 psig. This is a standard safety setting to prevent system overpressure while avoiding unnecessary releases during normal operation."},{"id":"type3-007","group":"type3","question":"Which of the following components is only found in Type 3 appliances?","choices":["Compressor","Purge Unit","Condenser","Evaporator"],"answer":1,"explanation":"The Purge Unit is the only component found exclusively in Type 3 appliances."},{"id":"type3-008","group":"type3","question":"Which of the following i is not a Type 3 frigerant","choices":["R-11","R-22","R-123","R-1233zd"],"answer":1,"explanation":"R-22 is a Type 2 high-pressure refrigerant."},{"id":"type3-009","group":"type3","question":"Which of the following refrigerants would be used in a low-pressure appliance?","choices":["R-22","R-123","R-410A","R-407A"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Among the options provided, R-123 is the refrigerant used in low- pressure appliances. It is specifically classified as a low-pressure refrigerant."},{"id":"type3-010","group":"type3","question":"You've pressurized a chiller tube with colored water using a tube test kit. Which result confirms the tube is leaking?","choices":["Dye seeping out and visible color marking","Asteady gauge reading with clear water","Vapor at the vent with no dye trace","No dye movement and no external marks"],"answer":0,"explanation":"A hydrostatic tube test kit uses colored water under pressure; dye oozing and visible colored marks identify the leak path."},{"id":"type3-011","group":"type3","question":"With the water side drained, why is the drain valve opening the preferred spot to sample with a leak detector?","choices":["It is the warmest point, boosting detector sensitivity","It sits farthest from the rupture disc seal","Itreduces noise from the vent valve area","It's the lowest port where leaked vapor gathers"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Once drained, any leaked refrigerant can migrate to the lowest opening, so placing a leak detector probe in the drain valve opening gives the best chance to detect it."},{"id":"type3-012","group":"type3","question":"Continuous excessive moisture collection in which component of a low-pressure refrigeration system could indicate a leak?","choices":["Water Box","Purge Unit","Drain Valve Outlet","Pressure Relief Valve"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Excessive moisture collection in the purge unit could indicate that the condenser or the chiller barrel tubes are leaking and drawing water into the system"},{"id":"type3-013","group":"type3","question":"After pulling a low-pressure chiller down to 1mm Hg, the reading climbs to 2.7 mm Hg over a short hold. What is the compliant next step according to ASHRAE?","choices":["Proceed to charge; rise is still acceptable","Repeat evacuation and ignore the pressure rise","Perform additional leak checking before any charging","Add nitrogen to 12 psig to stabilize"],"answer":2,"explanation":"ASHRAE Guidelines 3 states that if the pressure in the system rises from 1mm Hg to a level above 2.5 mm Hg during vacuum testing, the system should be further leak-checked."},{"id":"type3-014","group":"type3","question":"When leak testing a low-pressure refrigeration system with nitrogen, exceeding [blank] psig could cause the [blank] to fail.","choices":["30; Condenser tubes","30; Purge unit shells","10; Rupture disc","20; Evaporator tubes"],"answer":2,"explanation":"While leak testing a low-pressure chiller with nitrogen, the maximum pressure should not exceed 10 psig. If it exceeds 10 psig, the rupture disc will burst open."},{"id":"type3-015","group":"type3","question":"Where does water usually leak into low-pressure chillers?","choices":["Tube leaks","Relief valve","Failed condenser gasket","Service ports"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Water most commonly leaks into low-pressure chillers through a failed condenser gasket because the inside is below atmospheric pressure. Tube leaks or valve failure are less common causes."},{"id":"type3-016","group":"type3","question":"A belt-driven non-hermetic compressor has sat idle for months and leaks on startup. What condition most likely explains the leakage?","choices":["Suction service valve packing swelled under deep vacuum","Rubber in the rotating shaft seal hardened and lost sealing","Piston rings eroded due to long-term moisture exposure","Threads on the king valves expanded and loosened under"],"answer":1,"explanation":"If a belt-driven non-hermetic compressor has not been used for several months, the rubber seals in the rotating shaft may harden and fail to seal the system properly."},{"id":"type3-017","group":"type3","question":"On January 10, 2024, an HVAC servicing company disposes of a rooftop unit containing 35 Ib of refrigerant. Until what date must the company retain the disposal records at minimum?","choices":["January 10,2026","January 10,2027","January 10,2028","January 10,2025"],"answer":1,"explanation":"An HVAC servicing company that disposes of an appliance with a charge between 5 and 50 pounds must keep the records for a minimum period of 3 years. From January 10, 2024, years is January 10, 2027."},{"id":"type3-018","group":"type3","question":"A low-pressure chiller with a full charge >200 Ib is found leaking on June 15, 2024. The owner chooses a replacement that uses a refrigerant that is exempt from venting prohibitions. By what date must the unit be retired or retrofitted?","choices":["June 15,2025","March 15,2026","September 15,2025","December 15,2025"],"answer":3,"explanation":"EPA regulations normally allow 12 months for retrofit or retirement after exceeding leak thresholds. However, if the replacement i system will use a refrigerant exempt from venting prohibitions (such as R-717 or R-744), the deadline extends to 18 months from the leak , discovery date. June 15, 2024 + 18 months = December 15, 2025."},{"id":"type3-019","group":"type3","question":"How long must owners and operators of low-pressure chillers using R11 refrigerant keep records of leak inspections, initial verification, and follow-up verification tests?","choices":["2 years","3 years","5 years","Life of the appliance"],"answer":1,"explanation":"As per the EPA, it is compulsory to keep the records for any appliance containing 50 or more pounds refrigerant for a minimum of 3 years."},{"id":"type3-020","group":"type3","question":"How long must owners and operators of regulated appliances normally containing 50 or more pounds of CFC refrigerant keep records of leak inspections, initial leak verification, and follow-up verification tests?","choices":["2 years","3 years","5 years","Life of the appliance"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Owners and operators of regulated appliances containing 50 or more pounds of regulated refrigerant should maintain all records for at least 3 years."},{"id":"type3-021","group":"type3","question":"During a service call on a 60-Ib system, you must verify ether he annual leak rate exceeds the EPA limit before topping off. To do that, you first need the system's full charge. According to EPA rules, which methods may be used to determine the full charge?","choices":["Calculations based on power consumption, in kWh","Calculations based on tonnage","Calculations based on component and pipe sizes","Calculations based on the BTU capacity of the system"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Component and pipe sizes to determine the full charge in the system"},{"id":"type3-022","group":"type3","question":"Which of the following situations does qualify for an extension of a leak-repair deadline?","choices":["No tech available to visit site","Owner wants to delay repair","Budget approval still pending","Critical part is not available"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Extensions are allowed for specific constraints like documented part unavailability, not for staffing, budget, or convenience."},{"id":"type3-023","group":"type3","question":"In which of the following cases will charging a system that contains 50+ pounds of ozone-depleting refrigerant require you to calculate its leak rate?","choices":["Following a retrofit","During the installation of a new appliance","During a qualified seasonal variance","When topping off the system"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The requirement to calculate the leak rate is triggered when topping off fefrigerant, regardless of the specific scenario."},{"id":"type3-024","group":"type3","question":"When disposing of an HVAC appliance with 10 pounds of refrigerent, what is one EPA-mandated recordkeeping requirement?","choices":["Do not include refrigerant type in records","Only keep electronic records at headquarters","Keep disposal records for at least 3 years","Retain records for less than 1 year"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Disposal records for appliances with 5-50 pounds refrigerant must be kept for at least 3 years."},{"id":"type3-025","group":"type3","question":"Why do recovery units used on low-pressure chillers include a high-pressure cut-out set near the 10 psig range?","choices":["To increase flow rate through the recovery compressor","Tokeep the purge unit operating continuously","To prevent the rupture disc from bursting as pressure climbs","To maintain constant superheat at the condenser outlet"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Low-pressure chillers have rupture discs that can open around 10-15 psig; the cut-out on recovery units prevents exceeding ~10 psig and protects the system."},{"id":"type3-026","group":"type3","question":"You're beginning recovery on a low-pressure chiller at ambient conditions. To follow best practice, you should:","choices":["Open the purge and hold at O psig","Pump out liquid first, then recover vapor","Pump out vapor first, then recover liquid","Add heat, then pull vapor only"],"answer":1,"explanation":"Refrigerant removal from a low-pressure system typically begins with the removal of liquid refrigerant and then finishes with the removal of vapor."},{"id":"type3-027","group":"type3","question":"Why use a water-cooled recovery unit?","choices":["Easier transport","Lower cost","Faster recovery","No power required"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Water-cooled units allow faster recovery."},{"id":"type3-028","group":"type3","question":"In the case of confirmed leaks during refrigerant recovery in a chiller, what must be done?","choices":["Drain water from condenser and evaporator barrels","Increase system pressure","Bypass the recovery unit","Leave water inside the system"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Water must be drained from the condenser and evaporator to prevent mixing impurities with refrigerant during recovery."},{"id":"type3-029","group":"type3","question":"What is a requirement for equipment used for recovery, evacuation, and troubleshooting purposes, manufactured after November 15, 1993?","choices":["They must be equipped with high-pressure cut-out controls","They must have pressure gauges with high-pressure readings","They must be fitted with low-loss fittings","They must include additional recovery hoses for redundancy"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Any equipment manufactured after November 15, 1993, for these purposes must be equipped with low-loss fittings to ensure efficient and environmentally friendly operation."},{"id":"type3-030","group":"type3","question":"While evacuating a low-pressure chiller with no confirmed tube leaks, the water pump is accidentally switched off. As recovery continues, the barrel temperature keeps dropping. What is the immediate risk if you do not restore water circulation?","choices":["Loss of recovered mass to the purge unit &","Sudden rise in refrigerant pressure above setpoint G:","Ice formation that can damage tubes and pumps","Loss of vacuum due to air diffusion"],"answer":2,"explanation":"With no leaks present, water must keep moving during evacuation to avoid freezing and equipment damage."},{"id":"type3-031","group":"type3","question":"What risk is associated with attempting to melt ice formed in the chiller system after charging with liquid refrigerant?","choices":["Increased energy consumption","Increased compressor wear and tear","Risk of rupture and bursting of coils","Decreased cooling efficiency"],"answer":2,"explanation":"Charging liquid refrigerant under a high vacuum can cause ice formation in the system. Attempting to melt this ice may lead to coil damage and refrigerant leaks."},{"id":"type3-032","group":"type3","question":"While charging a water-cooled, low-pressure chiller after evacuation, which indicator tells you it's safe to switch from vapor to liquid charging?","choices":["Saturation temperature increases above 32°F","Suction pressure falls below 10 in Hg absolute","Cylinder scale shows 15 minutes of steady mass flow","Discharge superheat increases by 10°F from baseline"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Keep vapor-charging until system pressure corresponds to a saturation temperature around 32°F (=0°C). That threshold puts you above the freezing risk before introducing liquid."},{"id":"type3-033","group":"type3","question":"Identify the recovery requirements for equipment disposal","choices":["0 psig","15 inches of Hg vacuum","25 inches of Hg vacuum","25mm of Hg absolute"],"answer":3,"explanation":"The EPA requires systems to be evacuated to mm Hg absolute (nearly a perfect vacuum) before equipment disposal. This standard ensures almost all refrigerant is recovered and prevents environmental harm."},{"id":"type3-034","group":"type3","question":"Water present in the system can freeze if?","choices":["A large vacuum pump is used for evacuation","A recovery unit is used for evacuation","The system's compressor is used for evacuation","Ahouse vacuum cleaner is used for evacuation"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Water in the system can freeze if a large vacuum pump is used during evacuation, as the rapid decrease in pressure and temperature can lead to ice formation."},{"id":"type3-035","group":"type3","question":"To introduce initial refrigerant vapor from the lowest point on a centrifugal chiller, which service connection should be used?","choices":["Evaporator charging valve","Condenser service valve","Compressor cooler jacket","Purge unit exhaust port"],"answer":0,"explanation":"The evaporator charging valve is the lowest access point on all centrifugal chillers and air-conditioning appliances."},{"id":"type3-036","group":"type3","question":"During the evacuation of a moisture-laden chiller, the vacuum stalls and frost begins to form in the piping. What action should the technician take to restore flow without adding refrigerant?","choices":["Add a small refrigerant charge to warm the lines, then pull again","Run the compressor to heat the circuit before continuing evacuation","Open the system to room air to equalize pressure and temperature","Break the vacuum with a brief nitrogen sweep, then resume evacuation"],"answer":3,"explanation":"Introducing nitrogen raises pressure and temperature, preventing freezing of the moisture inside the system. After the brief nitrogen sweep, resume evacuation to remove both the nitrogen and the moisture."},{"id":"type3-037","group":"type3","question":"After confirming a leak, a technician is scheduled to replace an evaporator coil on a low-pressure chiller. Under EPA rules, this job is classified as a:","choices":["Major repair","Emergency service","Minor repair","System-dependent repair"],"answer":0,"explanation":"According to EPA regulations, a major repair involves the removal of specific components such as the condenser, evaporator, auxiliary heat exchanger coil, or compressor. Thus, replacing an evaporator coil falls under the major repair category."},{"id":"type3-038","group":"type3","question":"A mechanical room contains equipment using A1, A2L, and B2 refrigerants. To comply with ASHRAE Stand ard 15-2013, the refrigerant alarm system must detect leaks from:","choices":["A1 refrigerants","B2 refrigerants","A2 refrigerants","All refrigerant safety groups"],"answer":3,"explanation":"ASHRAE Stand ard 15-2013 requires the use of room sensors and alarms to detect leaks of refrigerant belonging to all safety groups. Detection isn't limited to one class."},{"id":"type3-039","group":"type3","question":"According to ASHRAE Stand ard 15-2013, which equipment is mandated to detect refrigerant leaks?","choices":["Room Sensors","Mechanical Ventilators","Pollution Detectors","Air purifiers with HEPA filters"],"answer":0,"explanation":"ASHRAE Stand ard 15-2013 requires equipment rooms to be equipped with electronic refrigerant detectors, also known as room sensors, to detect refrigerant leaks."},{"id":"type3-040","group":"type3","question":"During a design review, a junior technician proposes installing two pressure relief valves in series on the discharge line \"for extra safety.\" The correct response is:","choices":["Not allowed; relief valves must never be installed in series","Allowed if the valves are the same capacity","Allowed with annual testing and documentation","Required on systems with very large charges"],"answer":0,"explanation":"Pressure relief valves should never be installed in series to the system lines. It doesn't add protection and can cause improper discharge."},{"id":"type3-041","group":"type3","question":"What is the main function of isopropyl alcohol in refrigeration systems?","choices":["To regulate the pressure while evacuation","Toremove air from the filter drier","To remove ice off the sight glass","To vent the refrigerant"],"answer":2,"explanation":"The purpose of isopropyl alcohol is to remove ice from the sight glass."},{"id":"type3-042","group":"type3","question":"If a unit experiences a compressor burnout, we would collect an [blank] as part of a [blank]","choices":["refrigerant sample; major repair","air sample; minor repair","oil sample; major repair","oil sample; normal repair"],"answer":2,"explanation":"When a compressor burnout occurs, it is considered a major repair according to EPA regulations. In such cases, taking an oil sample is essential to assess the condition of the refrigerant oil."}]};
